{"title_page": "Vic Feazell", "text_new": "{{short description|American lawyer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{like-resume|date=December 2019}}\n{{refimprove-BLP|date=December 2019}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Vic Feazell 2019.jpg|thumb|Vic Feazell in front of the McLennan County Courthouse, Waco TX]]\n'''Vic Feazell''' is an American lawyer, who was a [[District attorney|District Attorney]] in [[Waco, Texas|Waco]], [[McLennan County, Texas|McLennan County]] from 1983 until his resignation in 1988. During his time in office he was involved in the investigation and prosecution of the [[1982 Lake Waco murders]] and also several crimes to which [[Henry Lee Lucas]] had been linked. Feazell currently resides in Waco, [[Texas]], and is an [[Lawyer|attorney]] with his own firm. He is known for his [[Television advertisement|commercials]] sporting the \"Drive Laid Back\" [[slogan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.withviclegal.com/attorneys/vic-feazell/#TabPanel-0|title=Austin Personal Injury Lawyer {{!}} Vic Feazell|last=|first=|date=|website=Law Offices of Vic Feazell, P.C.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d0UbAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1605|title=Official Gazette of the United States Patent and Trademark Office: Trademarks|date=2005|publisher=U.S. Department of Commerce, Patent and Trademark Office|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nFeazell was raised in Texas. At 17 years old, he took the [[Civil service entrance examination|civil service exam]] and was hired by the [[Austin Police Department]]. In the early 1970s, Feazell graduated from [[University of Mary Hardin\u2013Baylor|University of Mary Hardin Baylor]] and attended [[Baylor Law School]], receiving his J.D. in May 1979.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.withviclegal.com/attorneys/vic-feazell/|title=Austin Personal Injury Lawyer {{!}} Vic Feazell|website=Law Offices of Vic Feazell, P.C.|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref> Ten days after [[graduation]] from law school, Feazell [[Trial|tried]] his first [[jury trial]], alone, and [[Victory|won]] it.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n==Career==\nFeazell announced his candidacy for District Attorney of McLennan County in Waco, Texas in 1982. He would go on to win the election against the incumbent district attorney and became one of the youngest to hold the position in McLennan County. During his first term as District Attorney, Feazell tried the 1982 [[Lake Waco]] Triple Murders. In 1984, a [[jury]] found David Wayne Spence guilty of the murders and sentenced him to the [[Capital punishment|death penalty]]. A chronicle of the Lake Waco Murders can be found in the [[Edgar Award]]-winning book ''Careless Whispers'' by Carlton Stowers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/236856-careless-whispers|title=Careless Whispers|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref> Feazell notes on his website that he is \"now a vocal advocate against the death penalty.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.withviclegal.com/attorneys/vic-feazell/|title=Austin Personal Injury Lawyer {{!}} Vic Feazell|website=Law Offices of Vic Feazell, P.C.|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, after [[Henry Lee Lucas]] claimed to have killed over 300 people across the country, the [[Texas Ranger Division|Texas Rangers]] announced numerous murders to have been solved. Three of these announced murders were in McLennan County. This prompted Feazell to begin investigating the claims. This resulted in the Lucas Report. The report suggested that Lucas could not have committed some of the murders to which he had confessed.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lrl.texas.gov/scanned/archive/2009/8145.pdf|title=1845.pdf Lucas Report|last=Mattox|first=Jim|date=|website=Legislative Reference Library of Texas|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n{{Clarify|reason=|date=December 2019}} A decision afterwards resulted in Feazell's arrest.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} There were nineteen agents in town for Feazell's arrest and the search of his office and home.\n\nFeazell's arrest came seven weeks before election day. Voters in McLennan County re-elected Feazell for another term. During the criminal investigation leading up to Feazell's indictment, a reporter from [[Dallas]] television station [[WFAA|WFAA-TV]] named Charles Duncan ran an eleven-part series about Feazell, which later led to a libel judgement in favor of Feazell worth $58 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/8ddec8414352efb89896c04ae7bd2cd2|title=Settlement Reached In Record $58 Million Libel Judgment|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-12-29-mn-2104-story.html|title=Killer's Case a True Trial for Texas D.A.|date=1991-12-29|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> This series was the only evidence shown to the [[Grand juries in the United States|federal grand jury]] that indicted Feazell.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dmagazine.com/publications/d-magazine/1985/october/war-in-waco/|title=WAR IN WACO|website=D Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref> Feazell was found not guilty of all charges on June 29, 1987. Feazell then returned to work as District Attorney of McLennan County. On September 13, 1988, Feazell sent out a [[press release]] stating he would be resigning as District Attorney.\n\nFeazell then began representing Lucas in all of the still-pending murder cases he had confessed to around the country.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} Feazell spent much of the 1990s representing Lucas to ensure he was not convicted based on any more false confessions. The work done by Feazell and others cast enough doubt on the validity of the Lucas confession to the [[Murder of Debra Jackson|Orange Socks murder case]] that in 1998 then-[[Governor]] [[George W. Bush]] [[Pardon|commuted]] Lucas's death penalty to life imprisonment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pmc.iath.virginia.edu/issue.501/11.3knox.html|title=Knox, The Productive Power of Confessions of Cruelty|website=pmc.iath.virginia.edu|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcentv.com/article/news/crime/1979-orange-socks-cold-case-victim-identified-as-debra-jackson-of-abilene/269-376d1bed-b35a-49ab-b3cf-12c73358cb8a|title=1979 'Orange Socks' cold case victim identified as Debra Jackson of Abilene|website=KCEN|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, represented by former [[United States Attorney|U.S. Attorney]] [[Gary Richardson (lawyer)|Gary Richardson]], Feazell was awarded a $58 million judgment for [[Defamation|libel]] charges against [[WFAA|WFAA-TV]], at the time the largest libel judgment in [[History of the United States|U.S. history]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1991/04/20/Jury-awards-58-million-libel-judgment/6599672120000/|title=Jury awards $58 million libel judgment|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref> As a result, he was cited in the 1993 edition of [[Guinness World Records]] for largest defamation lawsuit in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.withviclegal.com/blog/2015/january/vic-feazell-recognized-in-guinness-book-of-world/|title=Defamation|publisher=[[Guinness World Records]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the 21st century, Feazell formed his own [[Law firm|law office]], The Law Offices of Vic Feazell with offices presently in [[Austin, Texas|Austin]] and Waco, Texas. The offices work primarily with [[Personal injury lawyer|personal injury]] cases and occasionally criminal cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.withviclegal.com/about-the-firm/|title=About the Firm|website=Law Offices of Vic Feazell, P.C.|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|http://www.vicfeazell.com}}\n*[https://www.withviclegal.com/ Austin law firm website]\n*[https://waco.withviclegal.com/ Waco law firm website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Feazell, Vic}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Waco, Texas]]\n[[Category:County district attorneys in Texas]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n{{US-law-bio-stub}}\n{{US-crime-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American lawyer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{like-resume|date=December 2019}}\n{{refimprove-BLP|date=December 2019}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Vic Feazell 2019.jpg|thumb|Vic Feazell in front of the McLennan County Courthouse, Waco TX]]\n'''Vic Feazell''' is an American lawyer, who was a [[District attorney|District Attorney]] in [[Waco, Texas|Waco]], [[McLennan County, Texas|McLennan County]] from 1983 until his resignation in 1988. During his time in office he was involved in the investigation and prosecution of the [[1982 Lake Waco murders]] and also several crimes to which [[Henry Lee Lucas]] had been linked. Feazell currently resides in Waco, [[Texas]], and is an [[Lawyer|attorney]] with his own firm. He is known for his [[Television advertisement|commercials]] sporting the \"Drive Laid Back\" [[slogan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.withviclegal.com/attorneys/vic-feazell/#TabPanel-0|title=Austin Personal Injury Lawyer {{!}} Vic Feazell|last=|first=|date=|website=Law Offices of Vic Feazell, P.C.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d0UbAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA1605|title=Official Gazette of the United States Patent and Trademark Office: Trademarks|date=2005|publisher=U.S. Department of Commerce, Patent and Trademark Office|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nFeazell was raised in Texas. At 17 years old, he took the [[Civil service entrance examination|civil service exam]] and was hired by the [[Austin Police Department]]. In the early 1970s, Feazell graduated from [[University of Mary Hardin\u2013Baylor|University of Mary Hardin Baylor]] and attended [[Baylor Law School]], receiving his J.D. in May 1979.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.withviclegal.com/attorneys/vic-feazell/|title=Austin Personal Injury Lawyer {{!}} Vic Feazell|website=Law Offices of Vic Feazell, P.C.|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref> Ten days after [[graduation]] from law school, Feazell [[Trial|tried]] his first [[jury trial]], alone, and [[Victory|won]] it.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n==Career==\nFeazell announced his candidacy for District Attorney of McLennan County in Waco, Texas in 1982. He would go on to win the election against the incumbent district attorney and became one of the youngest to hold the position in McLennan County. During his first term as District Attorney, Feazell tried the 1982 [[Lake Waco]] Triple Murders. In 1984, a [[jury]] found David Wayne Spence guilty of the murders and sentenced him to the [[Capital punishment|death penalty]]. A chronicle of the Lake Waco Murders can be found in the [[Edgar Award]]-winning book ''Careless Whispers'' by Carlton Stowers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/236856-careless-whispers|title=Careless Whispers|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref> Feazell notes on his website that he is \"now a vocal advocate against the death penalty.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.withviclegal.com/attorneys/vic-feazell/|title=Austin Personal Injury Lawyer {{!}} Vic Feazell|website=Law Offices of Vic Feazell, P.C.|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, after [[Henry Lee Lucas]] claimed to have killed over 300 people across the country, the [[Texas Ranger Division|Texas Rangers]] announced numerous murders to have been solved. Three of these announced murders were in McLennan County. This prompted Feazell to begin investigating the claims. This resulted in the Lucas Report. The report suggested that Lucas could not have committed some of the murders to which he had confessed.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lrl.texas.gov/scanned/archive/2009/8145.pdf|title=1845.pdf Lucas Report|last=Mattox|first=Jim|date=|website=Legislative Reference Library of Texas|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=}}</ref>\n\n{{Clarify|reason=|date=December 2019}} A decision afterwards resulted in Feazell's arrest.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} There were nineteen agents in town for Feazell's arrest and the search of his office and home.\n\nFeazell's arrest came seven weeks before election day. Voters in McLennan County re-elected Feazell for another term. During the criminal investigation leading up to Feazell's indictment, a reporter from [[Dallas]] television station [[WFAA|WFAA-TV]] named Charles Duncan ran an eleven-part series about Feazell, which later led to a libel judgement in favor of Feazell worth $58 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/8ddec8414352efb89896c04ae7bd2cd2|title=Settlement Reached In Record $58 Million Libel Judgment|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1991-12-29-mn-2104-story.html|title=Killer's Case a True Trial for Texas D.A.|date=1991-12-29|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> This series was the only evidence shown to the [[Grand juries in the United States|federal grand jury]] that indicted Feazell.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dmagazine.com/publications/d-magazine/1985/october/war-in-waco/|title=WAR IN WACO|website=D Magazine|language=en|access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref> Feazell was found not guilty of all charges on June 29, 1987. Feazell then returned to work as District Attorney of McLennan County. On September 13, 1988, Feazell sent out a [[press release]] stating he would be resigning as District Attorney.\n\nFeazell then began representing Lucas in all of the still-pending murder cases he had confessed to around the country.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} Feazell spent much of the 1990s representing Lucas to ensure he was not convicted based on any more false confessions. The work done by Feazell and others cast enough doubt on the validity of the Lucas confession to the [[Murder of Debra Jackson|Orange Socks murder case]] that in 1998 then-[[Governor]] [[George W. Bush]] [[Pardon|commuted]] Lucas's death penalty to life imprisonment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pmc.iath.virginia.edu/issue.501/11.3knox.html|title=Knox, The Productive Power of Confessions of Cruelty|website=pmc.iath.virginia.edu|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kcentv.com/article/news/crime/1979-orange-socks-cold-case-victim-identified-as-debra-jackson-of-abilene/269-376d1bed-b35a-49ab-b3cf-12c73358cb8a|title=1979 'Orange Socks' cold case victim identified as Debra Jackson of Abilene|website=KCEN|access-date=2019-08-07}}</ref>\n\nIn 1991, represented by former [[United States Attorney|U.S. Attorney]] [[Gary Richardson]], Feazell was awarded a $58 million judgment for [[Defamation|libel]] charges against [[WFAA|WFAA-TV]], at the time the largest libel judgment in [[History of the United States|U.S. history]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1991/04/20/Jury-awards-58-million-libel-judgment/6599672120000/|title=Jury awards $58 million libel judgment|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=2019-08-05}}</ref> As a result, he was cited in the 1993 edition of [[Guinness World Records]] for largest defamation lawsuit in history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.withviclegal.com/blog/2015/january/vic-feazell-recognized-in-guinness-book-of-world/|title=Defamation|publisher=[[Guinness World Records]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the 21st century, Feazell formed his own [[Law firm|law office]], The Law Offices of Vic Feazell with offices presently in [[Austin, Texas|Austin]] and Waco, Texas. The offices work primarily with [[Personal injury lawyer|personal injury]] cases and occasionally criminal cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.withviclegal.com/about-the-firm/|