|Socialist Workers]]) 0.1%<br> [[Lawrence Aeshliman]] (Constitution) 0.1%\n|-\n|'''[[2002 Nebraska gubernatorial election|Nebraska]]'''\n|'''[[Mike Johanns]]'''\n|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|Re-elected, 68.9%\n|[[Stormy Dean]] (Democratic) 27.5% <br> [[Paul Rosberg]] (Nebraska) 3.8%\n|-\n|'''[[2002 Nevada gubernatorial election|Nevada]]'''\n|'''[[Kenny Guinn]]'''\n|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|Re-elected, 68.3%\n|[[Joe Neal]] (Democratic) 22% <br> [[None of the above]] 4.7% <br> [[Dick Geyer]] (Libertarian) 1.6% <br> [[David Holmgren (politician)|David Holmgren]] ([[Independent American Party of Nevada|Indep. American]]) 1.4% <br> [[Jerry Norton (politician)|Jerry Norton]] (Independent) 1.1% <br> [[Charles Laws]] (Green) 1%\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFB3B3\" \n|'''[[2002 New Hampshire gubernatorial election|New Hampshire]]'''\n| bgcolor=\"lightgrey\" | [[Jeanne Shaheen]]\n|[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|Retired, Republican victory\n|'''[[Craig Benson]]''' (Republican) 58.6% <br> [[Mark Fernald]] (Democratic) 38.2% <br> [[John Babiarz]] (Libertarian) 2.9%\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\" \n|'''[[2002 New Mexico gubernatorial election|New Mexico]]'''\n| bgcolor=\"lightgrey\" | [[Gary Johnson]]\n|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|Term-limited, Democratic victory\n|'''[[Bill Richardson]]''' (Democratic) 56% <br> [[John Sanchez]] (Republican) 39% <br> [[David Bacon (politician)|David Bacon]] (Green) 5%<ref name=\"cnn-results-no-1st-names\">{{Cite news\n |title=CNN.com Election 2002 \u2013 Governor\n |url=http://edition.cnn.com/ELECTION/2002/pages/governor/index.html\n |publisher=[[Cable News Network|CNN]]\n |year=2002\n |accessdate=2011-04-19}}</ref>\n|-\n|'''[[2002 New York gubernatorial election|New York]]'''\n|'''[[George Pataki]]'''\n|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], [[Conservative Party of New York|Conservative]]\n|Re-elected, 49.4%\n|[[Carl McCall]] (Democratic), ([[Working Families Party|W