erm-limited, Republican victory\n|'''[[Donald Carcieri|Don Carcieri]]''' (Republican) 54.8% <br> [[Myrth York]] (Democratic) 45.2%\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFB3B3\" \n|'''[[2002 South Carolina gubernatorial election|South Carolina]]'''\n|[[Jim Hodges]]\n|[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|Defeated, 47.1%\n|'''[[Mark Sanford]]''' (Republican) 52.9%\n|-\n|'''[[2002 South Dakota gubernatorial election|South Dakota]]'''\n| bgcolor=\"lightgrey\" | [[Bill Janklow]]\n|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|Term-limited, Republican victory\n|'''[[Mike Rounds]]''' (Republican) 56.8% <br> [[James W. Abbott|Jim Abbott]] (Democratic) 41.9% <br> [[James Carlson]] (Independent) 0.7%<br> [[Nathan Barton]] (Libertarian) 0.6%\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\" \n|'''[[2002 Tennessee gubernatorial election|Tennessee]]'''\n| bgcolor=\"lightgrey\" | [[Don Sundquist]]\n|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|Term-limited, Democratic victory\n|'''[[Phil Bredesen]]''' (Democratic) 50.7% <br> [[Van Hilleary]] (Republican) 47.6%\n|-\n|'''[[2002 Texas gubernatorial election|Texas]]'''\n|'''[[Rick Perry]]'''\n|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|Re-elected, 57.8%\n|[[Tony Sanchez (politician)|Tony Sanchez]] (Democratic) 40%<br>[[Jeff Daiell]] (Libertarian) 1.6% <br> [[Rahul Mahajan (blogger)|Rahul Mahajan]] (Green) 1%\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFB3B3\" \n|'''[[2002 Vermont gubernatorial election|Vermont]]'''\n| bgcolor=\"lightgrey\" | [[Howard Dean]]\n|[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|Retired, Republican victory\n|'''[[Jim Douglas]]''' (Republican) 44.9% <br> [[Doug Racine]] (Democratic) 42.4% <br> [[Cornelius Hogan (politician)|Cornelius Hogan]] (Independent) 9.7%<br> [[Cris Ericson]] (Make Marijuana Legal) 0.8%<br> [[Michael Badamo]] ([[Vermont Progressive Party|VT Progressive]]) 0.6% <br> [[Joel Williams (politician)|Joel Williams]] (Libertarian) 0.4%<br>[[Patricia Hejny]] (VT Grassroots) 0.3%<br> [[Marilynn Christian]] (Restore Justice-Freedom) 0.3%<br>[[Pete Diamondstone]] ([[Liberty Union Party|Liberty Union]]) 0.3%\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\" \n| '''[[2002 Wisconsin gubernatorial election|Wisconsin]]''' \n|[[Scott McCallum]]\n|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|Defeated, 41.4%\n|'''[[Jim Doyle]]''' (Democratic) 45.1% <br> [[Ed Thompson]] (Libertarian) 10.5% <br> [[Jim Young (politician)|Jim Young]] (Green) 2.5%\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\" \n|'''[[2002 Wyoming gubernatorial election|Wyoming]]'''\n| bgcolor=\"lightgrey\" | [[Jim Geringer]]\n|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|Term-limited, Democratic victory\n|'''[[Dave Freudenthal]]''' (Democratic) 50% <br> [[Eli Bebout]] (Republican) 47.9% <br> [[Dave Dawson (Wyoming politician)|Dave Dawson]] (Libertarian) 2.12%\n|}\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|- bgcolor=#cccccc\n! Territory\n! Incumbent\n! Party\n! Status\n! Competing candidates\n|- {{party shading/Republican}}\n|'''[[2002 Guamanian general election|Guam]]''' \n| bgcolor=\"lightgrey\" | [[Carl Gutierrez]]\n|[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|Term-limited, Republican victory\n| '''[[Felix Perez Camacho]]''' (Republican) 55.4%<br> [[Robert A. Underwood|Robert Underwood]] (Democratic) 44.6%\n|-\n|[[United States Virgin Islands]]<ref>http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=39489</ref>\n| '''[[Charles Wesley Turnbull|Charles Turnbull]]'''\n|[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|Re-elected, 50.15%\n|[[John de Jongh]] (Independent) 24.64%<br> [[Chucky Hansen]] (Independent) 7.76%<br> [[Michael Bornn]] (Republican) 7.18%<br> [[Gerard Luz James|Gerard James]] (Independent) 5.07%<br> [[Cora Christian]] (Independent) 3.06%<br> [[Lloyd L. Williams|Lloyd Williams]] (Independent) 1.48%<br>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2002 United States elections]]\n**[[2002 United States Senate elections]]\n**[[2002 United States House of Representatives elections]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://edition.cnn.com/ELECTION/2002/pages/governor/index.html Election 2002 \u2013 Governor]. CNN.\n\n{{United States general elections, 2002}}\n{{USGovElections}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:United States Gubernatorial Elections, 2002}}\n[[Category:2002 elections in the United States|Gubernatorial]]\n[[Category:Gubernatorial elections in the United States by year|2002]]\n[[Category:2002 United States gubernatorial elections| ]]\n[[Category:November 2002 events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{More footnotes|date=April 2011}}\n{{Infobox election\n|election_name      = 2002 United States gubernatorial elections\n|country            = United States\n|type               = legislative\n|ongoing            = no\n|previous_election  = 2001 United States gubernatorial elections\n|previous_year      = 2001\n|next_election      = 2003 United States gubernatorial elections\n|next_year          = 2003\n|seats_for_election = 38 governorships <br> 36 states; 2 territories\n|election_date      = November 5, 2002\n|image1             = [[File:John Rowland (cropped).jpg|x165px]]\n|leader1            = [[John G. Rowland|John Rowland]]\n| leaders_seat1      = [[Connecticut]]\n|party1             = Republican Party (United States)\n|last_election1     = 30 governorships (27 states)\n|seats_before1      = '''30 (27 states)'''\n|seats_after1       = '''29 (26 states)'''\n|seat_change1       = {{decrease}}1\n|image2             = [[File:Parris Glendening speaking, September 2006 (cropped).jpg|x165px]]\n|leader2            = [[Parris Glendening]]\n| leaders_seat2      = [[Maryland]]\n|party2             = Democratic Party (United States)\n|last_election2     = 26 governorships (21 states)\n|seats_before2      = 26 (21 states)\n|seats_after2       = 27 (22 states)\n|seat_change2       = {{increase}}1\n|map_image          = 2002 Gubernatorial election map.svg\n|map_size           = 320px\n|map_caption        = <big>'''Results:'''{{Legend|#800|Republican hold}}{{Legend|#f00|Republican gain}}{{Legend|#008|Democratic hold}}{{Legend|#00f|Democratic gain}}</big>\n}}\n'''United States gubernatorial elections''' were held on November 5, 2002 in 36 states and two [[Unincorporated territories of the United States|territories]]. The [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] won eight seats previously held by the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]], as well as the seat previously held by Minnesota governor [[Jesse Ventura]], who was elected on the [[Reform Party (United States)|Reform Party]] ticket but had since renounced his party affiliation. The Democrats won 10 seats previously held by the Republicans, as well as the seat previously held by Maine governor [[Angus King]], an [[Independent politician|independent]]. Overall, the Republicans suffered a net loss of one seat while the Democrats made a net gain of three. The Republicans managed to maintain their majority of state governorships, but it was reduced to a margin of only two seats. The elections were notable for the sheer number of state governorships that changed parties \u2013 20 in total, constituting more than half of the seats up for election. Additionally, a number of Democratic and Republican gains occurred in states that typically favor the other party; for instance, Republican candidates won the usually Democratic states of Maryland, Hawaii, Minnesota and Vermont, while Democratic governors were elected in Republican-leaning states like Wyoming, Tennessee, Oklahoma and Kansas. \n\nIn addition to the elections held in 36 [[U.S. state|states]], elections were also held in the [[Unincorporated territories of the United States|unincorporated territories]] of [[Guam]] and the [[United States Virgin Islands]]. The Democrats held their seat in the United States Virgin Islands, while the Republicans won an open seat in Guam previously held by the Democrats.\n\nThe elections were held concurrently with the other [[United States elections, 2002|United States elections of 2002]].\n\nThis election marked the most recent cycle in which New York and Colorado elected Republican governors.\n\n==Democratic gains==\n* [[Arizona]] \u2013 State Attorney General [[Janet Napolitano]] won an open seat held by term-limited Gov. [[Jane Dee Hull]].\n* [[Illinois]] \u2013 U.S. Representative [[Rod Blagojevich]] won an open seat held by retiring Gov. [[George H. Ryan]], becoming the first Democratic governor of Illinois since 1976.\n* [[Kansas]] \u2013 State Insurance Commissioner [[Kathleen Sebelius]] won an open seat held by term-limited Gov. [[Bill Graves]].\n* [[Maine]] \u2013 U.S. Representative [[John Baldacci]] won an open seat held by Independent term-limited Gov. [[Angus King]].\n* [[Michigan]] \u2013 State Attorney General [[Jennifer Granholm]] won an open seat held by term-limited Gov. [[John Engler]].\n* [[New Mexico]] \u2013 former U.S. Representative and U.S. Secretary of Energy [[Bill Richardson]] won an open seat held by term-limited Gov. [[Gary Johnson]].\n* [[Oklahoma]] \u2013 State Senator [[Brad Henry]] won an open seat held by term-limited Gov. [[Frank Keating]].\n* [[Pennsylvania]] \u2013 former Mayor of [[Philadelphia]] and DNC Chairman [[Ed Rendell]] won an open seat held by retiring Gov. Mark Schweiker.\n* [[Tennessee]] \u2013 former [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] Mayor [[Phil Bredesen]] won an open seat held by term-limited Gov. [[Don Sundquist]].\n* [[Wisconsin]] \u2013 State Attorney General [[Jim Doyle]] '''''defeated''''' incumbent Gov. [[Scott McCallum]]\n* [[Wyoming]] \u2013 U.S. Attorney [[Dave Freudenthal]] won an open seat held by term-limited Gov. [[Jim Geringer]].\n\n==Republican gains==\n* [[Alabama]] \u2013 U.S. Representative [[Bob Riley]] narrowly '''''defeated''''' incumbent Gov. [[Don Siegelman]].\n* [[Alaska]] \u2013 U.S. Senator [[Frank Murkowski]] won an open seat held by term-limited Gov. [[Tony Knowles (politician)|Tony Knowles]].\n* [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] \u2013 [[Georgia State Senate|State Senator]] [[Sonny Perdue]] '''''defeated''''' incumbent Gov. [[Roy Barnes]] and became first Republican Governor of Georgia since the 1870s.\n* [[Guam]] \u2013 [[Legislature of Guam|Territorial Legislative]] Majority Leader [[Felix Perez Camacho]] won an open seat held by term-limited Gov. [[Carl T.C. Gutierrez]].\n* [[Hawaii]] \u2013 Former Maui Mayor [[Linda Lingle]] won an open seat held by term-limited Gov. [[Benjamin Cayetano]], becoming the first Republican Governor since 1962.\n* [[South Carolina]] \u2013 U.S. Representative [[Mark Sanford]] '''''defeated''''' incumbent Gov. [[Jim Hodges]].\n* [[Maryland]] \u2013 U.S. Representative [[Robert Ehrlich]] won an open seat held by term-limited Gov. [[Parris Glendening]], becoming the first Republican Governor since [[Spiro Agnew]] in 1966.\n* [[Minnesota]] \u2013 State House Majority Leader [[Tim Pawlenty]] won an open seat held by retiring Independent Gov. [[Jesse Ventura]] in difficult, three-way (GOP, DFL and IMP) race.\n* [[New Hampshire]] \u2013 Businessman [[Craig Benson]] won an open seat held by retiring Gov. [[Jeanne Shaheen]].\n* [[Vermont]] \u2013 State Treasurer [[Jim Douglas]] won an open seat held by retiring Gov. [[Howard Dean]].\n\n==Election results==\nA bolded state name features an article about the specific election.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! State\n! Incumbent\n! Party\n! Status\n! Opposing candidates\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFB3B3\"\n| '''[[2002 Alabama gubernatorial election|Alabama]]'''\n| [[Don Siegelman]]\n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| Defeated, 49.0%\n| '''[[Bob Riley]]''' ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) 49.2%<br>[[John Sophocleus]] ([[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]) 1.7%\n|- bgcolor=\"#FFB3B3\"\n| '''[[2002 Alaska gubernatorial election|Alaska]]'''\n| bgcolor=\"lightgrey\" | [[Tony Knowles (politician)|Tony Knowles]]\n| [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n| Term-limited, Republican victory\n| '''[[Frank Murkowski]]''' (Republican) 55.8%<br>[[Fran Ulmer]] (Democratic) 40.7%<br>[[Diane E. Benson|Diane Benson]] ([[Green Party (United States)|Green]]) 1.3%<br>[[Don Wright (politician)|Don Wright]] ([[Alaskan Independence Party|Alaskan Indep.]])<br>[[Raymond VinZant]] ([[Republican Moderate Party of Alaska|Rep. Mod.]]) 0.7%<br>[[Billy Toien]] (Libertarian) 0.5%\n|- bgcolor=\"lightblue\"\n| '''[[2002 Arizona gubernatorial election|Arizona]]'''\n| bgcolor=\"lightgrey\" | [[Jane Dee Hull|Jane Hull]]\n| [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| Term-limited, Democratic victory\n| '''[[Janet Napolitano]]''' (Democratic) 46.2%<br> [[Matt Salmon]] (Republican) 45.2%<br>[[Richard D. Mahoney]] (Independent) 6.9%<br> [[Barry Hess]] (Libertarian) 1.7%\n|- \n| '''[[2002 Arkansas gubernatorial election|Arkansas]]'''\n| '''[[Mike Huckabee]]'''\n| [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| Re-elected, 53%\n| [[Jimmie Lou Fisher]] (Democratic) 46%<br>\n|- \n| '''[[2002 California gubernatorial election|California]]'''\n| '''[[Gray Davis]]'''\n| [[California Democratic Party|Democratic]]\n| Re-elected, 47.4%\n| [[Bill Simon (politician)|Bill Simon]] ([[California Republican Party|Republican]]) 42.4%<br>[[Peter Camejo]] ([[Green Party of California|Green]]) 5.3%<br>[[Gary Copeland]] ([[Libertarian Party of California|Libertarian]]) 2.2%<br>[[Reinhold Gulke]] ([[American Independent Party|American Ind.]]) 1.7%<br>[[Iris Adam]] ([[Natural Law Party|Natural Law]]) 1.1%\n|-\n|'''[[2002 Colorado gubernatorial election|Colorado]]'''\n|'''[[Bill Owens (Colorado politician)|Bill Owens]]'''\n|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|Re-elected, 62.6%\n|[[Rollie Heath]] (Democratic) 33.7% <br> [[Ronald Forthofer]] (Green) 2.3% <br> [[Ralph Shnelvar]] (Libertarian) 1%\n|-\n|'''[[2002 Connecticut gubernatorial election|Connecticut]]''' \n|'''[[John G. Rowland|John Rowland]]''' \n|[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] \n|Re-elected, 56.1% \n|[[Bill Curry (politician)|Bill Curry]] (Democratic) 43.9% \n|- \n|'''[[2002 Florida gubernatorial election|Florida]]''' 