04-4|ref={{sfnRef|Hedgepeth|2010}}}}\n*{{cite book|author=Alexis Demirdjian|title=The Armenian Genocide Legacy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1L3tCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA125|date=4 April 2016|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-137-56163-3|ref={{sfnRef|Demirdjian|2016}}}}\n*{{cite book|author=Kerry F. Crawford|title=Wartime Sexual Violence: From Silence to Condemnation of a Weapon of War|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rUowDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA13|year=2017|publisher=Georgetown University Press|isbn=978-1-62616-466-6|ref={{sfnRef|Crawford|2017}}}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Mary Michele Connellan|author2=Christiane Fr\u00f6hlich|title=A Gendered Lens for Genocide Prevention|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WB4xDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA142|date=15 August 2017|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|isbn=978-1-137-60117-9|ref={{sfnRef|Connellan|2017}}}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Larry Collins|author2=Dominique Lapierre|title=Freedom at Midnight|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.103056/page/n359/mode/2up|year=1975|publisher=Collins|isbn=978-0-00-216055-1| ref = {{sfnRef|Collins|1975}}}}\n*{{cite book|author=Yasmin Khan|title=The Great Partition: The Making of India and Pakistan|url=https://archive.org/details/greatpartitionma00khan|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/greatpartitionma00khan/page/n180 135]|year=2007|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=0-300-12078-8| ref = {{sfnRef|Khan|2007}}}}\n*{{cite book|author=Bina D Costa|title=Nationbuilding, Gender and War Crimes in South Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ivzKjY5LncIC&pg=PA102|year=2010|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9780415565660| ref = {{sfnRef|D'Costa|2010}}}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Ritu Menon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yNN4SE7cL60C&pg=PA70|title=Borders & Boundaries: Women in India's Partition|author2=Kamla Bhasin|publisher=Rutgers University Press|year=1998|isbn=978-0-8135-2552-5| ref = {{sfnRef|Menon|1998}}}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Major |first1=Andrew |title=Abduction of women during the partition of the Punjab |journal=South Asia: Journal of South Asian Studies |date=1995 |volume=18 |issue=1 |doi=10.1080/00856409508723244| ref = {{sfnRef|Major|1995}}}}\n*{{cite book|author=Amal Kumar Chattopadhyay|title=Slavery in India; with an introduction by Radha Kumud Mukherjee and with a foreword by Asim Kumar Datta|url=https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.105457/page/n165/mode/2up|year=1959|publisher=Nagarjun Press|ref={{sfnRef|Chattopadhyay|1959}}}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Jacqueline Suthren Hirst|author2=John Zavos|title=Religious Traditions in Modern South Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bBOpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA152|date=March 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-62668-5| ref = {{sfnRef|Hirst|2013}}}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Gyanendra Pandey|author2=Professor of History Gyanendra Pandey|title=Remembering Partition: Violence, Nationalism and History in India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZdLhnFet4w4C&pg=PA165|date=22 November 2001|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-00250-9|ref = {{sfnRef|Pandey|2001}}}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Barbara D. Metcalf|author2=Thomas R. Metcalf|title=A Concise History of Modern India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c7UgAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA226|date=24 September 2012|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-53705-6| ref = {{sfnRef|Metcalf|2012}}}}\n*{{cite journal |title= Islam's Black Slaves: The Other Black Diaspora by Ronald Segal- Book Review |journal=The Journal of Blacks in Higher Education |date=2001 |number=31 | ref = {{sfnRef|Islam's Black Slaves|2001}}}}\n*{{cite book|author=Jok Madut Jok|title=War and Slavery in Sudan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wqzvlWdxThwC|date=3 August 2010|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=0-8122-0058-6| ref ={{sfnRef|Jok|2010}}}}\n*{{cite book|author=N. Nojumi|title=The Rise of the Taliban in Afghanistan: Mass Mobilization, Civil War, and the Future of the Region|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=h18YDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA168|date=30 April 2016|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan US|isbn=978-0-312-29910-1| ref = {{sfnRef|Nojumi|2016}}}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Peter J. Claus|author2=Sarah Diamond|author3=Margaret Ann Mills|title=South Asian Folklore: An Encyclopedia : Afghanistan, Bangladesh, India, Nepal, Pakistan, Sri Lanka|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ienxrTPHzzwC&pg=PA7|year=2003|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-93919-5| ref = {{sfnRef|Claus|2003}}}}\n*{{cite book|author=Jacqueline L. Hazelton|title=Beyond Slavery: Overcoming Its Religious and Sexual Legacies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NaVhAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT3|date=25 October 2010|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-0-230-11389-3| ref = {{sfnRef|Hazelton|2010}}}}\n*{{cite journal |last1=Ali |first1=Kecia |title=Redeeming Slavery: The \u2018Islamic State\u2019 and the Quest for Islamic Morality |journal=Mizan: Journal for the Study of Muslim Societies and Civilizations |date=2016 |volume=1 |issue=1  |url=https://mizanproject.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/02-Mizan-Journal-Vol-1_Issue-1_Ali_Redeeming-Slavery.pdf| ref = {{sfnRef|Ali|2016}}}}\n*{{cite book|author1=William Gervase Clarence-Smith|author2=W. G. Clarence-Smith|title=Islam and the Abolition of Slavery|url=https://archive.org/details/islamabolitionof0000clar|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/islamabolitionof0000clar/page/n56 27]|year=2006|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-522151-0| ref = {{sfnRef|Smith|2006}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:Groups practising sexual slavery]]\n[[Category:Concubinage]]\n[[Category:Wartime sexual violence]]\n[[Category:Violence against women]]\n[[Category:Slavery]]\n", "name_user": "Mcphurphy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMiddle East:c/e", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sexual_slavery_in_Islam"}
{"title_page": "Nassarius horridus", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image =Hebra horrida 001.jpg\n| image_caption = A collection of shells of ''Nassarius horridus'' (museum specimens at Naturalis Biodiversity Center)\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Mollusca]]\n| classis = [[Gastropoda]]\n| unranked_superfamilia = clade [[Caenogastropoda]]<br/>clade [[Hypsogastropoda]]<br/>clade [[Neogastropoda]]\n| superfamilia = [[Buccinoidea]]\n| familia = [[Nassariidae]]\n| subfamilia =\n| genus = ''[[Nassarius]]''\n| species = '''''N. horridus'''''\n| binomial = ''Nassarius horridus''\n| binomial_authority = (Dunker, 1847)\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"WoRMS\" />\n| synonyms =\n{{collapsible list|bullets = true |title=<small>list of synonyms</small> \n| ''Buccinum horridum'' <small>Dunker, 1847</small>(original combination)\n| ''Buccinum muricatum'' <small>Quoy & Gaimard, 1882</small> (invalid: junior homonym of ''Buccinum muricatum'' <small>Lightfoot, 1786</small>)\n* Buccinum scabrum Dunker, 1846 (Invalid: junior homonym of ''Buccinum scabrum'' <small>Anton, 1838</small>)\n| ''Hebra curta'' <small>(Gould, 1850)</small>\n| ''Hebra horrida'' <small>(Dunker, 1847)</small>\n| ''Nassa (Hebra) horrida'' <small>(Dunker, 1847)</small>\n| ''Nassa (Hebra) muricata'' <small>(Quoy & Gaimard, 1833)</small>\n| ''Nassa curta'' <small>Gould, 1850</small>\n| ''Nassa horrida'' <small>(Dunker, 1847)</small>\n| ''Nassa muricata'' <small>(Quoy & Gaimard, 1882)</small>\n| ''Nassa muricata'' var. ''horrida'' <small>(Dunker, 1847)</small>\n| ''Scabronassa horrida'' <small>(Dunker, 1847)</small>}}\n}}\n\n'''''Nassarius horridus''''', common name the '''horrid nassa''', is a [[species]] of [[sea snail]], a marine [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Nassariidae]], the Nassa mud snails or dog whelks.<ref name=\"WoRMS\">Marshall, B. (2016). Nassarius horridus (Dunker, 1847). In: MolluscaBase (2016). Accessed through: World Register of Marine Species at http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=215735 on 2016-05-19</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe length of the shell varies between 8&nbsp;mm and 15&nbsp;mm.\n\nThe small shell is ovate, subglobular, and spined. The [[Spire (mollusc)|spire]] is conical and pointed. It is composed of six or seven [[Whorl (mollusc)|whorl]]s. The [[body whorl]] is much larger than all the others. The spire presents on its exterior longitudinal folds, upon which are regularly disposed pointed, conical tubercles, which are of the same color as the rest of the shell. The first row of these spines is situated immediately beneath the suture. The last one obliquely intersects the base of the shell. Transverse striae, pretty fine and numerous, are observed between each of the rows of the spines. The white [[Aperture (mollusc)|aperture]] is semilunar. The outer [[Lip (gastropod)|lip]] is thick and furnished internally with fine striae.  The [[Columella (gastropod)|columella]] is nearly straight, covered by the inner lip which forms a callosity. The color is uniform, of a white fawn, sometimes pale orange.<ref name=\"Kiener\">[https://archive.org/details/generalspeciesic00kien Kiener (1840). General species and iconography of recent shells : comprising the Massena Museum, the collection of Lamarck, the collection of the Museum of Natural History, and the recent discoveries of travellers; Boston :W.D. Ticknor,1837] (described as  ''Buccinum muricatum'' Quoy & Gaimard, 1882)</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThis marine species occurs off [[Durban]], Rep. South Africa, off East Africa; [[Madagascar]], [[R\u00e9union]], [[Aldabra]]; and in the Indo-West Pacific: [[East India]] , Western [[Thailand]], [[Papua New Guinea]], [[Indonesia]], the [[Philippines]], Indo-Malaysia, [[Ryukyu Islands]], [[Solomon Islands]], [[Marshall Islands]], [[New Hebrides]], [[New Caledonia]], [[Loyalty Islands]], [[Fiji]], [[Tonga]], [[Samoan Islands]], [[Caroline Islands]]; and off Australia ([[Northern Territory]], [[Queensland]], [[Western Australia]]).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Dunker, G. 1847. ''Diagnoses Buccinorum quorundam novorum''. Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Malakozoologie 4: 59\u201364\n* Quoy, J.R.C. & Gaimard, J.P. 1833. ''Voyage de d\u00e9couvertes de l'Astrolabe, ex\u00e9cut\u00e9 par ordre du Roi, pendant les ann\u00e9es 1826\u20131829''. Paris : J. Tastu Zoologie Vol. 2 pp.&nbsp;321\u2013686.\n* Gould, A.A. 1850. ''Descriptions of the shells brought home by the U.S. Exploring Expedition'' (cont.). Proceedings of the Boston Society of Natural History 3: 151\u2013156  \n* Cernohorsky, W.O. 1984. ''Systematics of the family Nassariidae (Mollusca: Gastropoda)''. Bulletin of the Auckland Institute and Museum. Auckland, New Zealand 14: 1\u2013356\n* Wilson, B. 1994. ''Australian Marine Shells. Prosobranch Gastropods.'' Kallaroo, WA : Odyssey Publishing Vol. 2 370 pp.\n* Higo, S., Callomon, P. & Goto, Y. 1999. ''Catalogue and Bibliography of the Marine Shell-bearing Mollusca of Japan''. Japan : Elle Scientific Publications 749 pp.\n* Marais J.P. & Kilburn R.N. (2010) Nassariidae. pp.&nbsp;138\u2013173, in: Marais A.P. & Seccombe A.D. (eds), ''Identification guide to the seashells of South Africa. Volume 1''. Groenkloof: Centre for Molluscan Studies. 376 pp.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gastropods.com|key=2|id=3312|title=''Hebra horrida''|access-date=16 January 2019}}\n{{Commons category|Hebra horrida}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5695802}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nassarius Horridus}}\n[[Category:Nassariidae]]\n[[Category:Gastropods described in 1847]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Taxobox\n| image =Hebra horrida 001.jpg\n| image_caption = A collection of shells of ''Nassarius horridus'' (museum specimens at Naturalis Biodiversity Center)\n| regnum = [[Animal]]ia\n| phylum = [[Mollusca]]\n| classis = [[Gastropoda]]\n| unranked_superfamilia = clade [[Caenogastropoda]]<br/>clade [[Hypsogastropoda]]<br/>clade [[Neogastropoda]]\n| superfamilia = [[Buccinoidea]]\n| familia = [[Nassariidae]]\n| subfamilia =\n| genus = ''[[Nassarius]]''\n| species = '''''N. horridus'''''\n| binomial = ''Nassarius horridus''\n| binomial_authority = (Dunker, 1847)\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=\"WoRMS\" />\n| synonyms =\n{{collapsible list|bullets = true |title=<small>list of synonyms</small> \n| ''Buccinum horridum'' <small>Dunker, 1847</small>(original combination)\n| ''Buccinum muricatum'' <small>Quoy & Gaimard, 1882</small> (invalid: junior homonym of ''Buccinum muricatum'' <small>Lightfoot, 1786</small>)\n* Buccinum scabrum Dunker, 1846 (Invalid: junior homonym of ''Buccinum scabrum'' <small>Anton, 1838</small>)\n| ''Hebra curta'' <small>(Gould, 1850)</small>\n| ''Hebra horrida'' <small>(Dunker, 1847)</small>\n| ''Nassa (Hebra) horrida'' <small>(Dunker, 1847)</small>\n| ''Nassa (Hebra) muricata'' <small>(Quoy & Gaimard, 1833)</small>\n| ''Nassa curta'' <small>Gould, 1850</small>\n| ''Nassa horrida'' <small>(Dunker, 1847)</small>\n| ''Nassa muricata'' <small>(Quoy & Gaimard, 1882)</small>\n| ''Nassa muricata'' var. ''horrida'' <small>(Dunker, 1847)</small>\n| ''Scabronassa horrida'' <small>(Dunker, 1847)</small>}}\n}}\n\n'''''Nassarius horridus''''', common name the '''horrid nassa''', is a [[species]] of [[sea snail]], a marine [[gastropod]] [[mollusk]] in the [[family (biology)|family]] [[Nassariidae]], the Nassa mud snails or dog whelks.<ref name=\"WoRMS\">Marshall, B. (2016). Nassarius horridus (Dunker, 1847). In: MolluscaBase (2016). Accessed through: World Register of Marine Species at http://www.marinespecies.org/aphia.php?p=taxdetails&id=215735 on 2016-05-19</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe length of the shell varies between 8&nbsp;mm and 15&nbsp;mm.\n\nThe small shell is ovate, subglobular, and spined. The [[Spire (mollusc)|spire]] is conical and pointed. It is composed of six or seven [[Whorl (mollusc)|whorl]]s. The [[body whorl]] is much larger than all the others. The spire presents on its exterior longitudinal folds, upon which are regularly disposed pointed, conical tubercles, which are of the same color as the rest of the shell. The first row of these spines is situated immediately beneath the suture. The last one obliquely intersects the base of the shell. Transverse striae, pretty fine and numerous, are observed between each of the rows of the spines. The white [[Aperture (mollusc)|aperture]] is semilunar. The outer [[Lip (gastropod)|lip]] is thick and furnished internally with fine striae.  The [[Columella (gastropod)|columella]] is nearly straight, covered by the inner lip which forms a callosity. The color is uniform, of a white fawn, sometimes pale orange.<ref name=\"Kiener\">[https://archive.org/details/generalspeciesic00kien Kiener (1840). General species and iconography of recent shells : comprising the Massena Museum, the collection of Lamarck, the collection of the Museum of Natural History, and the recent discoveries of travellers; Boston :W.D. Ticknor,1837] (described as  ''Buccinum muricatum'' Quoy & Gaimard, 1882)</ref>\n\n==Distribution==\nThis marine species occurs off [[Durban]], Rep. South Africa, off East Africa; [[Madagascar]], [[R\u00e9union]], [[Aldabra]]; and in the Indo-West Pacific: [[East India]] , Western [[Thailand]], [[Papua New Guinea]], [[Indonesia]], the [[Philippines]], Indo-Malaysia, [[Ryukyu Islands]], [[Solomon Islands]], [[Marshall Islands]], [[New Hebrides]], [[New Caledonia]], [[Loyalty Islands]], [[Fiji]], [[Tonga]], [[Samoan Islands]], [[Caroline Islands]]; and off Australia ([[Northern Territory]], [[Queensland]], [[Western Australia]]).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Dunker, G. 1847. ''Diagnoses Buccinorum quorundam novorum''. Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Malakozoologie 4: 59\u201364\n* Quoy, J.R.C. & Gaimard, J.P. 1833. ''Voyage de d\u00e9couvertes de l'Astrolabe, ex\u00e9cut\u00e9 par ordre du Roi, pendant les ann\u00e9es 1826-1829''. Paris : J. Tastu Zoologie Vol. 2 pp.&nbsp;321\u2013686.\n* Gould, A.A. 1850. ''Descriptions of the shells brought home by the U.S. Exploring Expedition'' (cont.). Proceedings of the Boston Society of Natural History 3: 151\u2013156  \n* Cernohorsky, W.O. 1984. ''Systematics of the family Nassariidae (Mollusca: Gastropoda)''. Bulletin of the Auckland Institute and Museum. Auckland, New Zealand 14: 1\u2013356\n* Wilson, B. 1994. ''Australian Marine Shells. Prosobranch Gastropods.'' Kallaroo, WA : Odyssey Publishing Vol. 2 370 pp.\n* Higo, S., Callomon, P. & Goto, Y. 1999. ''Catalogue and Bibliography of the Marine Shell-bearing Mollusca of Japan''. Japan : Elle Scientific Publications 749 pp.\n* Marais J.P. & Kilburn R.N. (2010) Nassariidae. pp.&nbsp;138\u2013173, in: Marais A.P. & Seccombe A.D. (eds), ''Identification guide to the seashells of South Africa. Volume 1''. Groenkloof: Centre for Molluscan Studies. 376 pp.\n\n==External links==\n* {{Gastropods.com|key=2|id=3312|title=''Hebra horrida''|access-date=16 January 2019}}\n{{Commons category|Hebra horrida}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5695802}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nassarius Horridus}}\n[[Category:Nassariidae]]\n[[Category:Gastropods described in 1847]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nassarius_horridus"}
{"title_page": "Henrietta Rodman", "text_new": "{{short description|American educator and feminist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Henrietta Rodman\n| image       = {{CSS image crop\n|Image = Henrietta Rodman from the George Grantham Bain Collection.jpg\n|bSize = 514\n|cWidth = 320\n|cHeight = 369\n|oTop = 25\n|oLeft = 85\n}}\n|image_upright=1.4\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1877|08|29}} \n| birth_place = [[Astoria, New York]], US\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1923|03|21|1877|08|29}} \n| other_names = Mrs. De Fremery\n| occupation  = Educator\n| known_for   = Feminist and labor activism\n}}\n'''Henrietta Rodman''' (August 29, 1877 &ndash; March 21, 1923) was an American educator and feminist.  She was active on behalf of married women teachers' rights to promotion and maternity leave.\n\n==Early life and education==\nHenrietta Rodman was born in [[Astoria, New York]], the daughter of Rev. Washington Rodman and Henrietta Blackwell Rodman.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=98UI8lfyWXgC&lpg=PA74 |first=Sandra |last=Adickes|title=To Be Young was Very Heaven:  Women in New York before the First World War|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |year=2000|isbn=978-0312223359|page=74}}</ref>  Her father was a [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Protestant Episcopal]] clergyman in [[West Farms, Bronx]], and founder of [[St Barnabas Hospital (Bronx)|St. Barnabas Hospital]] in the Bronx.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uJRPAAAAMAAJ&lpg=PA116 |first=Charles Henry |last=Jones|title=Genealogy of the Rodman Family, 1620&ndash;1886|publisher=Allen, Lane & Scott|year=1886|page=116}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbhny.org/index.php/about_us/history |title=History|publisher=SBH Health System|year=2014}}</ref> She was a 1904 graduate of [[Teachers College, Columbia University]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fhiZFpE77tkC&lpg=PA335 |first=Rosalind |last=Rosenberg|authorlink=Rosalind Rosenberg|title=Changing the Subject: How the Women of Columbia Shaped the Way we Think About Sex and Politics|publisher=Columbia University Press |year=2013|isbn=978-0231501149|page=116}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRodman taught English and was a vocational counselor at [[Wadleigh High School for Girls]] in [[New York City]].<ref>Rodman, Henrietta. [https://books.google.com/books?id=2GVLAAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA101 \"Self-Analysis by High School Girls\"], in ''Proceedings of the Second National Conference on Vocational Guidance'', October 23&ndash;26, 1912. Volume 2, p. 101.</ref><ref>[[Emma Goldman]]'s essay [https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Social_Significance_of_the_Modern_Drama \"The Social Importance of the Modern School\"] includes an anecdote about Rodman teaching literature, and getting in trouble for discussing [[George Eliot]]'s personal life.</ref>  Opposed to the school board's restrictive policies on married women teachers, she married a psychologist friend, Herman de Fremery (a.k.a. Herman Defrem), in February 1913, and announced it to the press, saying, \"If the married state affects a woman's work, the authorities can mark her accordingly.  If it does not affect her work, and if she is as good a teacher as she was before, she deserves promotion, if it comes to her.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F60F10FE3C5417738DDDA00994DB405B838DF1D3 |title=Aided Mrs. Edgell, Married Herself: Supposed Miss Rodman, Wadleigh High School Teacher, Admits She is Mrs. Fremery|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=19 March 1913}}</ref> She also referred to the Board of Education, in print, as \"mother baiters.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10F16F93F5C13738DDDAA0A94DA415B848DF1D3 |title=Try Miss Rodman For School Satire: Teacher Who Called Education Board 'Mother Baiters' Defends Right of Free Speech|newspaper=The New York Times|date=23 December 1914}}</ref> She was suspended according to [[New York City Board of Education]] policy; a well-publicized and lengthy appeal followed, serving Rodman's purpose by keeping the issue in headlines.<ref>Carter, Patricia. [http://us.macmillan.com/womeneducatorsleadersandactivists/TanyaFitzgerald  \"Henrietta Rodman and the Fight to Further Women's Economic Autonomy\"], in Tanya Fitzgerald and Elizabeth M. Smyth, eds., ''Women Educators, Leaders, and Activists: Educational Lives and Networks, 1900-1960''. 2014: Palgrave Macmillan, {{ISBN|1-137-30351-4}}.</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-hsXOoyG1O0C&lpg=PA120 |first=Patricia Anne |last=Carter|title=Everybody's Paid but the Teacher: The Teaching Profession and the Women's Movement|publisher=Teachers College Press |year=2002|isbn=978-0807742068|pages=118&ndash;122}}</ref>\n\nRodman was a member of the Liberal Club and of [[Heterodoxy (group)|Heterodoxy]].<ref>Churchill, Allen (1959). [https://books.google.com/books?id=fM7a-OBysYcC&lpg=PA277 \"The Female Reformed: Henrietta Rodman's M\u00e4dchen\"], in C\u00e9sar Gra\u00f1a and Marigay Gra\u00f1a, eds., ''On Bohemia: The Code of the Self-Exiled''. 1990: Transaction Publishers, {{ISBN|1412829984}}, pp. 277&ndash;279.</ref> She agitated in the Liberal Club for the inclusion of African-American members, and for support of feminist causes; in 1913 she was successful in leading the relocation of the Liberal Club to [[MacDougal Street]] in [[Greenwich Village]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CQzSGndHQCcC&lpg=PA168 |first=Ross |last=Wetzsteon|title=Republic of Dreams: Greenwich Village: The American Bohemia, 1910-1960|publisher=Simon and Schuster |year=2007|isbn=978-1416589518|pages=166\u2013168}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lkPGQBsKJxUC&lpg=PA116 |first=Lewis A. |last=Coser|authorlink=Lewis A. Coser|title=Men of Ideas|publisher=Simon and Schuster |year=1997|isbn=978-0684833286|page=116}}</ref>\n\nIn 1914 Rodman formed the Feminist Alliance, uniting several feminist causes to work together.  Rodman took special interest in the collective housing, childcare, and communal kitchens, following the writings of [[Charlotte Perkins Gilman]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10917FD3A5A12738FDDAD0A94D9405B858DF1D3 |first=George |last=MacAdam|title=Feminist Apartment House to Solve Baby Problem: Miss Henrietta Rodman, Whose Fight for the Teacher-Mother Aroused Widespread Interest, Does a Little Prophesying about the Mother of the Future|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 January 1915}}</ref> She made serious plans for an apartment building to demonstrate those feminist principles,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F4081FFD3C5D17738DDDAC0A94DC405B858DF1D3 |first=Laura |last=Fay-Smith|title=The Feminist Paradise Palace:  Miss Henrietta Rodman's Suggestion of an Apartment House for the Advanced Mother Rouses the Ire of an Unbeliever|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 April 1915}}</ref> hiring an architect and rounding up financial backers, but stiff opposition and the onset of war scuttled any chance of success.<ref>{{cite journal|first=June |last=Sochen|title=Henrietta Rodman and the Feminist Alliance, 1914-1917|journal=Journal of Popular Culture|volume=4|issue=1|date=Summer 1970|pages=57\u201365|doi=10.1111/j.0022-3840.1970.0401_57.x}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AQRjNcrk1hsC&lpg=PA197 |first=Dolores |last=Hayden|authorlink=Dolores Hayden|title=The Grand Domestic Revolution: A History of Feminist Designs for American Homes, Neighborhoods, and Cities|publisher=MIT Press|year=1982|isbn=978-0262580557|pages=197&ndash;201}}</ref>\n\nDuring World War I, she was a member of the executive board of the [[Woman's Peace Party]], and wrote and lectured on [[pacifism]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O_EoAAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA449 |first=Henrietta |last=Rodman|title=Should Mother Raise Boy as Soldier? No! as Citizen Says Henrietta Rodman|journal=Journal of the Switchmen's Union of North America|volume=18|year=1916|page=449&ndash;450}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPlaywright [[Floyd Dell]] said that Rodman \"had an extraordinary gift for stirring things up. Incredibly na\u00efve, preposterously reckless, believing wistfully in beauty and goodness, a Candide in petticoats and sandals.\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K8aMN50YOvkC&lpg=PA188 |first=Luther S. |last=Harris|title=Around Washington Square: An Illustrated History of Greenwich Village|publisher=JHU Press |year=2003|isbn=978-0801873416|pages=187&ndash;188}}</ref>  Her [[Bohemian]] public persona was considered eccentric at best: she wore sack-like dresses and sandals long before they were in fashion; her hair was bobbed; she smoked cigarettes.  She threw crowded dinner parties in her top-floor apartment; [[Mary Hunter Austin|Mary Austin]] recalled attending one such dinner, and meeting [[James Weldon Johnson]] there.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L1IsE4xyqD0C&lpg=PA347 |first=Mary |last=Austin|authorlink=Mary Hunter Austin|title=Earth Horizon|publisher=Houghton Mifflin |year=1932|page=347|isbn=9780865345393 }}</ref> [[Margaret Sanger]] also remembered attending a tea hosted by Henrietta Rodman, whom she called \"Feminist of Feminists\", in Rodman's [[Greenwich Village]] apartment.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IQKAfF_ycEoC&lpg=PA187 |first=Margaret|last=Sanger|authorlink=Margaret Sanger|title=The Autobiography of Margaret Sanger|publisher=Dover Publications |year=2012|isbn=978-0486120836|page=187}}</ref> \n\nDuring her marriage to Herman de Fremery, the couple lived with Herman's earlier common-law wife, in an apartment on [[Bank Street (Manhattan)|Bank Street]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YgALtJ2GKIUC&lpg=PA73 |first1=William B. |last1=Scott |first2=Peter M. |last2=Rutkoff|title=New York Modern: The Arts and the City|publisher=JHU Press|year=2001|isbn=978-0801867934|page=73}}</ref>\n\nRodman adopted two children and was known as \"Mrs. Rodman\" in her personal life.  She died after unsuccessful surgery for a brain tumor in March 1923, at age 45.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2014/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Call/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Call%201923/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Call%201923%20-%200300.pdf |title=Miss Rodman Improved|newspaper=[[New York Call]]|date=29 January 1923|page=7}}</ref>\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal | last = Carter | first = Patricia | title = Guiding the working-class girl: Henrietta Rodman's curriculum for the new woman, 1913 | journal = [[Frontiers: A Journal of Women Studies]] | volume = 38 | issue = 1 | pages = 124&ndash;155 | jstor = 10.5250/fronjwomestud.38.1.0124 | date = 2017 |url = http://muse.jhu.edu/article/653263 | ref = harv | doi = 10.5250/fronjwomestud.38.1.0124 }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|89218175}}\n\n[[Category:American women in World War I]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1923 deaths]]\n[[Category:Teachers College, Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Astoria, Queens]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodman, Henrietta}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American educator and feminist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Henrietta Rodman\n| image       = {{CSS image crop\n|Image = Henrietta Rodman from the George Grantham Bain Collection.jpg\n|bSize = 514\n|cWidth = 320\n|cHeight = 369\n|oTop = 25\n|oLeft = 85\n}}\n|image_upright=1.4\n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1877|08|29}} \n| birth_place = [[Astoria, New York]], US\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1923|03|21|1877|08|29}} \n| other_names = Mrs. De Fremery\n| occupation  = Educator\n| known_for   = Feminist and labor activism\n}}\n'''Henrietta Rodman''' (August 29, 1877 &ndash; March 21, 1923) was an American educator and feminist.  She was active on behalf of married women teachers' rights to promotion and maternity leave.\n\n==Early life and education==\nHenrietta Rodman was born in [[Astoria, New York]], the daughter of Rev. Washington Rodman and Henrietta Blackwell Rodman.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=98UI8lfyWXgC&lpg=PA74 |first=Sandra |last=Adickes|title=To Be Young was Very Heaven:  Women in New York before the First World War|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |year=2000|isbn=978-0312223359|page=74}}</ref>  Her father was a [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Protestant Episcopal]] clergyman in [[West Farms, Bronx]], and founder of [[St Barnabas Hospital (Bronx)|St. Barnabas Hospital]] in the Bronx.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uJRPAAAAMAAJ&lpg=PA116 |first=Charles Henry |last=Jones|title=Genealogy of the Rodman Family, 1620&ndash;1886|publisher=Allen, Lane & Scott|year=1886|page=116}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sbhny.org/index.php/about_us/history |title=History|publisher=SBH Health System|year=2014}}</ref> She was a 1904 graduate of [[Teachers College, Columbia University]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fhiZFpE77tkC&lpg=PA335 |first=Rosalind |last=Rosenberg|authorlink=Rosalind Rosenberg|title=Changing the Subject: How the Women of Columbia Shaped the Way we Think About Sex and Politics|publisher=Columbia University Press |year=2013|isbn=978-0231501149|page=116}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRodman taught English and was a vocational counselor at [[Wadleigh High School for Girls]] in [[New York City]].<ref>Rodman, Henrietta. [https://books.google.com/books?id=2GVLAAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA101 \"Self-Analysis by High School Girls\"], in ''Proceedings of the Second National Conference on Vocational Guidance'', October 23&ndash;26, 1912. Volume 2, p. 101.</ref><ref>[[Emma Goldman]]'s essay [https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Social_Significance_of_the_Modern_Drama \"The Social Importance of the Modern School\"] includes an anecdote about Rodman teaching literature, and getting in trouble for discussing [[George Eliot]]'s personal life.</ref>  Opposed to the school board's restrictive policies on married women teachers, she married a psychologist friend, Herman de Fremery (aka Herman Defrem), in February 1913, and announced it to the press, saying, \"If the married state affects a woman's work, the authorities can mark her accordingly.  If it does not affect her work, and if she is as good a teacher as she was before, she deserves promotion, if it comes to her.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F60F10FE3C5417738DDDA00994DB405B838DF1D3 |title=Aided Mrs. Edgell, Married Herself: Supposed Miss Rodman, Wadleigh High School Teacher, Admits She is Mrs. Fremery|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=19 March 1913}}</ref> She also referred to the Board of Education, in print, as \"mother baiters.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10F16F93F5C13738DDDAA0A94DA415B848DF1D3 |title=Try Miss Rodman For School Satire: Teacher Who Called Education Board 'Mother Baiters' Defends Right of Free Speech|newspaper=The New York Times|date=23 December 1914}}</ref> She was suspended according to [[New York City Board of Education]] policy; a well-publicized and lengthy appeal followed, serving Rodman's purpose by keeping the issue in headlines.<ref>Carter, Patricia. [http://us.macmillan.com/womeneducatorsleadersandactivists/TanyaFitzgerald  \"Henrietta Rodman and the Fight to Further Women's Economic Autonomy\"], in Tanya Fitzgerald and Elizabeth M. Smyth, eds., ''Women Educators, Leaders, and Activists: Educational Lives and Networks, 1900-1960''. 2014: Palgrave Macmillan, {{ISBN|1-137-30351-4}}.</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-hsXOoyG1O0C&lpg=PA120 |first=Patricia Anne |last=Carter|title=Everybody's Paid but the Teacher: The Teaching Profession and the Women's Movement|publisher=Teachers College Press |year=2002|isbn=978-0807742068|pages=118&ndash;122}}</ref>\n\nRodman was a member of the Liberal Club and of [[Heterodoxy (group)|Heterodoxy]].<ref>Churchill, Allen (1959). [https://books.google.com/books?id=fM7a-OBysYcC&lpg=PA277 \"The Female Reformed: Henrietta Rodman's M\u00e4dchen\"], in C\u00e9sar Gra\u00f1a and Marigay Gra\u00f1a, eds., ''On Bohemia: The Code of the Self-Exiled''. 1990: Transaction Publishers, {{ISBN|1412829984}}, pp. 277&ndash;279.</ref> She agitated in the Liberal Club for the inclusion of African-American members, and for support of feminist causes; in 1913 she was successful in leading the relocation of the Liberal Club to [[MacDougal Street]] in [[Greenwich Village]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CQzSGndHQCcC&lpg=PA168 |first=Ross |last=Wetzsteon|title=Republic of Dreams: Greenwich Village: The American Bohemia, 1910-1960|publisher=Simon and Schuster |year=2007|isbn=978-1416589518|pages=166\u2013168}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lkPGQBsKJxUC&lpg=PA116 |first=Lewis A. |last=Coser|authorlink=Lewis A. Coser|title=Men of Ideas|publisher=Simon and Schuster |year=1997|isbn=978-0684833286|page=116}}</ref>\n\nIn 1914 Rodman formed the Feminist Alliance, uniting several feminist causes to work together.  Rodman took special interest in the collective housing, childcare, and communal kitchens, following the writings of [[Charlotte Perkins Gilman]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F10917FD3A5A12738FDDAD0A94D9405B858DF1D3 |first=George |last=MacAdam|title=Feminist Apartment House to Solve Baby Problem: Miss Henrietta Rodman, Whose Fight for the Teacher-Mother Aroused Widespread Interest, Does a Little Prophesying about the Mother of the Future|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 January 1915}}</ref> She made serious plans for an apartment building to demonstrate those feminist principles,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F4081FFD3C5D17738DDDAC0A94DC405B858DF1D3 |first=Laura |last=Fay-Smith|title=The Feminist Paradise Palace:  Miss Henrietta Rodman's Suggestion of an Apartment House for the Advanced Mother Rouses the Ire of an Unbeliever|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 April 1915}}</ref> hiring an architect and rounding up financial backers, but stiff opposition and the onset of war scuttled any chance of success.<ref>{{cite journal|first=June |last=Sochen|title=Henrietta Rodman and the Feminist Alliance, 1914-1917|journal=Journal of Popular Culture|volume=4|issue=1|date=Summer 1970|pages=57\u201365|doi=10.1111/j.0022-3840.1970.0401_57.x}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AQRjNcrk1hsC&lpg=PA197 |first=Dolores |last=Hayden|authorlink=Dolores Hayden|title=The Grand Domestic Revolution: A History of Feminist Designs for American Homes, Neighborhoods, and Cities|publisher=MIT Press|year=1982|isbn=978-0262580557|pages=197&ndash;201}}</ref>\n\nDuring World War I, she was a member of the executive board of the [[Woman's Peace Party]], and wrote and lectured on [[pacifism]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O_EoAAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA449 |first=Henrietta |last=Rodman|title=Should Mother Raise Boy as Soldier? No! as Citizen Says Henrietta Rodman|journal=Journal of the Switchmen's Union of North America|volume=18|year=1916|page=449&ndash;450}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPlaywright [[Floyd Dell]] said that Rodman \"had an extraordinary gift for stirring things up. Incredibly na\u00efve, preposterously reckless, believing wistfully in beauty and goodness, a Candide in petticoats and sandals.\"<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K8aMN50YOvkC&lpg=PA188 |first=Luther S. |last=Harris|title=Around Washington Square: An Illustrated History of Greenwich Village|publisher=JHU Press |year=2003|isbn=978-0801873416|pages=187&ndash;188}}</ref>  Her [[Bohemian]] public persona was considered eccentric at best: she wore sack-like dresses and sandals long before they were in fashion; her hair was bobbed; she smoked cigarettes.  She threw crowded dinner parties in her top-floor apartment; [[Mary Hunter Austin|Mary Austin]] recalled attending one such dinner, and meeting [[James Weldon Johnson]] there.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L1IsE4xyqD0C&lpg=PA347 |first=Mary |last=Austin|authorlink=Mary Hunter Austin|title=Earth Horizon|publisher=Houghton Mifflin |year=1932|page=347|isbn=9780865345393 }}</ref> [[Margaret Sanger]] also remembered attending a tea hosted by Henrietta Rodman, whom she called \"Feminist of Feminists\", in Rodman's [[Greenwich Village]] apartment.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IQKAfF_ycEoC&lpg=PA187 |first=Margaret|last=Sanger|authorlink=Margaret Sanger|title=The Autobiography of Margaret Sanger|publisher=Dover Publications |year=2012|isbn=978-0486120836|page=187}}</ref> \n\nDuring her marriage to Herman de Fremery, the couple lived with Herman's earlier common-law wife, in an apartment on [[Bank Street (Manhattan)|Bank Street]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YgALtJ2GKIUC&lpg=PA73 |first1=William B. |last1=Scott |first2=Peter M. |last2=Rutkoff|title=New York Modern: The Arts and the City|publisher=JHU Press|year=2001|isbn=978-0801867934|page=73}}</ref>\n\nRodman adopted two children and was known as \"Mrs. Rodman\" in her personal life.  She died after unsuccessful surgery for a brain tumor in March 1923, at age 45.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2014/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Call/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Call%201923/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Call%201923%20-%200300.pdf |title=Miss Rodman Improved|newspaper=[[New York Call]]|date=29 January 1923|page=7}}</ref>\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite journal | last = Carter | first = Patricia | title = Guiding the working-class girl: Henrietta Rodman's curriculum for the new woman, 1913 | journal = [[Frontiers: A Journal of Women Studies]] | volume = 38 | issue = 1 | pages = 124&ndash;155 | jstor = 10.5250/fronjwomestud.38.1.0124 | date = 2017 |url = http://muse.jhu.edu/article/653263 | ref = harv | doi = 10.5250/fronjwomestud.38.1.0124 }}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|89218175}}\n\n[[Category:American women in World War I]]\n[[Category:American feminists]]\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1923 deaths]]\n[[Category:Teachers College, Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Astoria, Queens]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodman, Henrietta}}\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: aka->a.k.a.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henrietta_Rodman"}
{"title_page": "Chasseurs Ardennais", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=10th Regiment of the Line 1830-1933<br>Regiment of ''Chasseurs Ardennais'' 1933-2011<br>Battalion of ''Chasseurs Ardennais'' (2011-)\n|image=Image:Insigne chasseurs ardennais.png \n|image_size = 150px\n|caption=Cap badge of the Chasseurs Ardennais \n|dates=1933 \u2013 Present\n|country={{flagicon|Belgium}} [[Belgium]]\n|branch=[[Belgian Army|Land Component]]\n|type=[[Infantry]]\n|command_structure=[[Medium Brigade (Belgium)|Medium Brigade]]\n|role=[[Mechanized infantry|Mechanised infantry]]\n|garrison=[[Marche-en-Famenne]]\n|motto=''R\u00e9siste et Mords!''<br/><small>(\"Resist and bite!\")</small>\n|march=''Marche des Chasseurs ardennais''\n}}\nThe '''''Bataillon de Chasseurs Ardennais''''' ({{lang-en|Ardennes Chasseur Battalion}})) is an [[infantry]] formation in the [[Belgian Army|Land Component]] of the [[Military of Belgium|Belgian Armed Forces]]. The unit, currently at battalion strength, is a part of the [[Medium Brigade (Belgium)|Medium Brigade]]. \n\nWithin the context of military history, the French language term ''chasseur'' (literally \"hunter\") usually denotes [[light infantry|light]] or [[mounted infantry]].\n[[Image:Chasseursardennais.jpg|thumb|280px|A platoon of Chasseurs Ardennais parading in [[Bastogne]]]]\nThe unit was formed in 1933 when the 10th Regiment of the Line was renamed the ''Regiment de Chasseurs Ardennais'', which it remained until 2011 when it was reduced to a battalion.<ref name=milbe1>{{cite web|title=Historique des Chasseurs Ardennais|url=http://www.mil.be/armycomp/units/index.asp?LAN=fr&FILE=&ID=580&MENU=1351&PAGE=1|publisher= |website=mil.be|accessdate=13 December 2012}}</ref> It is named after, and based in, the heavily forested and hilly [[Ardennes]] region of [[Belgium]].\n\n==History==\nThe origin of the ''Chasseurs Ardennais'' started with a concept conceived in 1914 by Colonel Bremer and pushed further by [[General Hellebaut]] in 1928: the creation of a corps on the east border of Belgium, near [[weimar republic|Germany]], in order to protect against a German attack. \n\nOn 10 March 1933, [[Albert I of Belgium|King Albert I]] changed the unit's name from ''10e de ligne'' to ''R\u00e9giment des Chasseurs Ardennais''. Subsequently, these soldiers, stationed in [[Arlon]], wore the wild boar (emblem of the [[Ardennes]]) on their green berets. One regiment was not enough to hold the east lines, so in August 1934, the regiment was divided into three and a bicycle battalion was added. On 24 March 1937, three regiments were created: 1st, 2nd and 3rd ''R\u00e9giment des Chasseurs Ardennais'' they were located in Arlon, [[Bastogne]] and [[Vielsalm]]. Each unit was structured with one HQ battalion, three battalions to three companies of mixed cyclists (three ''packs'' of riflemen and three packs of MG) one motorcycle company each with each three motorbike squadrons, and one squadron with three [[Belgian combat vehicles of World War II#T15 light tank|T-15 tanks]]; one company with four [[T-13 tank destroyer|T-13 tanks]] armed with 47mm antitank cannons; and finally one medical company. On July 1, 1939, these were formed into a division. Following the [[mobilization]] of the Belgian Army in late 1939 this division comprised 35,000 men, and a second division of three more regiments was created.\n\n===Second World War===\nIn the [[Second World War]], the ''Chasseurs Ardennais'' took part in heavy fighting after Belgium was [[Battle of Belgium|invaded]] on 10 May 1940; the Germans noted the fierce resistance of the Belgians and the ''Chasseurs Ardennais'' were no exception. In one engagement a [[47 mm Anti-tank Gun Model 1931|47mm anti-tank gun]] destroyed or disabled five German tanks.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} ''Troupes d'Elite Volume 2''. Editions Atlas, 1986</ref> They fought so bravely that German general [[Erwin Rommel]] said, \"They are not men, they are green wolves.\" A unit of only 40 men held off the combined arms of the German forces, including General Rommel's famed armored \"[[Ghost Division]]\" for 18 days and only surrendered after running out of ammunition.\n\n==Battle honours==\n[[File:Chasseurs Ardennais.jpg|thumb|Soldiers of the Chasseurs Ardennais, pictured in 1940]]\nThe unit's flag carries the following citations:\n* Namur\n* Termonde\n* Yser\n* Esen\n* Kortemark\n* Ardennes\n* La Dendre 1940 \n* Vinkt\n\n==Uniform and insignia==\nThe Chasseurs Ardennais have, since their inception, worn a large green beret in addition to the uniform which the rest of the army wears. The insignia worn on the cap is the head of a [[wild boar]] which are found in the Ardennes region.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Chasseurs Ardennais}}\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.mil.be/armycomp/units/index.asp?LAN=nl&ID=580\n|title=R\u00e9giment de Chasseurs Ardennais\n|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Belgium)|Defence Belgium]]\n|accessdate=2007-09-03\n|language=Dutch| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070926225021/http://www.mil.be/armycomp/units/index.asp?LAN=nl&ID=580| archivedate= 26 September 2007 | url-status= live}}\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.mil.be/armycomp/units/index.asp?LAN=fr&ID=580\n|title=R\u00e9giment de Chasseurs Ardennais\n|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Belgium)|Defence Belgium]]\n|accessdate=2007-09-03\n|language=French| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070815221228/http://www.mil.be/armycomp/units/index.asp?LAN=fr&ID=580| archivedate= 15 August 2007 | url-status= live}}\n\n[[Category:Regiments of Belgium|Ardennian Rifles]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1933]]\n[[Category:1933 establishments in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Marche-en-Famenne]]\n[[Category:Boars in heraldry]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=10th Regiment of the Line 1830-1933<br>Regiment of ''Chasseurs Ardennais'' 1933-2011<br>Battalion of ''Chasseurs Ardennais'' (2011-)\n|image=Image:Insigne chasseurs ardennais.png \n|image_size = 150px\n|caption=Cap badge of the Chasseurs Ardennais \n|dates=1933 \u2013 Present\n|country={{flagicon|Belgium}} [[Belgium]]\n|branch=[[Belgian Army|Land Component]]\n|type=[[Infantry]]\n|command_structure=[[Medium Brigade (Belgium)|Medium Brigade]]\n|role=[[Mechanized infantry|Mechanised infantry]]\n|garrison=[[Marche-en-Famenne]]\n|motto=''R\u00e9siste et Mords!''<br/><small>(\"Resist and bite!\")</small>\n|march=''Marche des Chasseurs ardennais''\n}}\nThe '''''Bataillon de Chasseurs Ardennais''''' ([[French language|French]]: \"[[Ardennes]] ''[[Chasseur]]'' Battalion\") is an [[infantry]] formation in the [[Belgian Army|Land Component]] of the [[Military of Belgium|Belgian Armed Forces]]. The unit, currently at battalion strength, is a part of the [[Medium Brigade (Belgium)|Medium Brigade]]. \n\nWithin the context of military history, the French language term ''chasseur'' (literally \"hunter\") usually denotes [[light infantry|light]] or [[mounted infantry]].\n[[Image:Chasseursardennais.jpg|thumb|280px|A platoon of Chasseurs Ardennais parading in [[Bastogne]]]]\nThe unit was formed in 1933 when the 10th Regiment of the Line was renamed the ''Regiment de Chasseurs Ardennais'', which it remained until 2011 when it was reduced to a battalion.<ref name=milbe1>{{cite web|title=Historique des Chasseurs Ardennais|url=http://www.mil.be/armycomp/units/index.asp?LAN=fr&FILE=&ID=580&MENU=1351&PAGE=1|publisher= |website=mil.be|accessdate=13 December 2012}}</ref> It is named after, and based in, the heavily forested and hilly [[Ardennes]] region of [[Belgium]].\n\n==History==\nThe origin of the ''Chasseurs Ardennais'' started with a concept conceived in 1914 by Colonel Bremer and pushed further by [[General Hellebaut]] in 1928: the creation of a corps on the east border of Belgium, near [[weimar republic|Germany]], in order to protect against a German attack. \n\nOn 10 March 1933, [[Albert I of Belgium|King Albert I]] changed the unit's name from ''10e de ligne'' to ''R\u00e9giment des Chasseurs Ardennais''. Subsequently, these soldiers, stationed in [[Arlon]], wore the wild boar (emblem of the [[Ardennes]]) on their green berets. One regiment was not enough to hold the east lines, so in August 1934, the regiment was divided into three and a bicycle battalion was added. On 24 March 1937, three regiments were created: 1st, 2nd and 3rd ''R\u00e9giment des Chasseurs Ardennais'' they were located in Arlon, [[Bastogne]] and [[Vielsalm]]. Each unit was structured with one HQ battalion, three battalions to three companies of mixed cyclists (three ''packs'' of riflemen and three packs of MG) one motorcycle company each with each three motorbike squadrons, and one squadron with three [[Belgian combat vehicles of World War II#T15 light tank|T-15 tanks]]; one company with four [[T-13 tank destroyer|T-13 tanks]] armed with 47mm antitank cannons; and finally one medical company. On July 1, 1939, these were formed into a division. Following the [[mobilization]] of the Belgian Army in late 1939 this division comprised 35,000 men, and a second division of three more regiments was created.\n\n===Second World War===\nIn the [[Second World War]], the ''Chasseurs Ardennais'' took part in heavy fighting after Belgium was [[Battle of Belgium|invaded]] on 10 May 1940; the Germans noted the fierce resistance of the Belgians and the ''Chasseurs Ardennais'' were no exception. In one engagement a [[47 mm Anti-tank Gun Model 1931|47mm anti-tank gun]] destroyed or disabled five German tanks.<ref>{{in lang|fr}} ''Troupes d'Elite Volume 2''. Editions Atlas, 1986</ref> They fought so bravely that German general [[Erwin Rommel]] said, \"They are not men, they are green wolves.\" A unit of only 40 men held off the combined arms of the German forces, including General Rommel's famed armored \"[[Ghost Division]]\" for 18 days and only surrendered after running out of ammunition.\n\n==Battle honours==\n[[File:Chasseurs Ardennais.jpg|thumb|Soldiers of the Chasseurs Ardennais, pictured in 1940]]\nThe unit's flag carries the following citations:\n* Namur\n* Termonde\n* Yser\n* Esen\n* Kortemark\n* Ardennes\n* La Dendre 1940 \n* Vinkt\n\n==Uniform and insignia==\nThe Chasseurs Ardennais have, since their inception, worn a large green beret in addition to the uniform which the rest of the army wears. The insignia worn on the cap is the head of a [[wild boar]] which are found in the Ardennes region.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Chasseurs Ardennais}}\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.mil.be/armycomp/units/index.asp?LAN=nl&ID=580\n|title=R\u00e9giment de Chasseurs Ardennais\n|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Belgium)|Defence Belgium]]\n|accessdate=2007-09-03\n|language=Dutch| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070926225021/http://www.mil.be/armycomp/units/index.asp?LAN=nl&ID=580| archivedate= 26 September 2007 | url-status= live}}\n*{{cite web\n|url=http://www.mil.be/armycomp/units/index.asp?LAN=fr&ID=580\n|title=R\u00e9giment de Chasseurs Ardennais\n|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Belgium)|Defence Belgium]]\n|accessdate=2007-09-03\n|language=French| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070815221228/http://www.mil.be/armycomp/units/index.asp?LAN=fr&ID=580| archivedate= 15 August 2007 | url-status= live}}\n\n[[Category:Regiments of Belgium|Ardennian Rifles]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1933]]\n[[Category:1933 establishments in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Marche-en-Famenne]]\n[[Category:Boars in heraldry]]\n", "name_user": "CPA-5", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chasseurs_Ardennais"}
{"title_page": "Bobby Koelble", "text_new": "{{short description|American guitarist}}\n'''Bobby Koelble''' (born September 15, 1968) is an American guitarist who performs in the [[death metal]], [[Blues music|blues]], [[Funk music|funk]] and [[jazz]] genres, and as a freelance, studio musician. He is probably best known for his performances with the [[Death metal]] band [[Death (metal band)|Death]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metal-archives.com/artists/Bobby_Koelble/72714|title=Bobby Koelble - Encyclopaedia Metallum: The Metal Archives|website=www.metal-archives.com}}</ref><ref name=moapril26>{{cite web|url=https://www.orangeobserver.com/article/guitarist-bobby-koelble-explores-music-at-winter-parks-blue-bamboo-center-for-the-arts|title=Guitarist Bobby Koelble explores music at Winter Park\u2019s Blue Bamboo Center for the Arts|author=Tim Freed|work=Orange Observer|date=April 26, 2018|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref> The album he played on, ''[[Symbolic (Death album)|Symbolic]]'', was regarded by [[Joel McIver]] of British music magazine ''[[Record Collector]]'' \"as close to flawless as metal gets.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://recordcollectormag.com/reviews/symbolic|title=Death \u2013 Symbolic|work=[[Record Collector]]|first=Joel|last=McIver|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in [[Newark, New Jersey]], Koelble\u2019s family moved to central Florida when he was three years old. He began playing the organ when he was seven. By thirteen, Koelble transitioned to guitar, inspired by hard rock banks like [[Van Halen]] and [[AC/DC]]. His evolution into metal music was influenced by bands like [[Iron Maiden]], [[Mot\u00f6rhead]] and [[Judas Priest]].<ref name=moapril26/>\n\n==Education==\nKoelble graduated the [[Berklee College of Music]] with a bachelors\u2019 degree in performance.<ref name=ucf>{{cite web|url=https://music.cah.ucf.edu/staff.php?id=255|title=CF Music -  Faculty Page - Bobby Koeble|work=[[University of Central Florida]]|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nKoelble works on original projects, as a leader, and performs for other groups as freelancer, and in studio work.\n\n===Performance===\nKoelble is best known for his time in the latter years of Death (1994-1996), the influential band that defined death metal.\n\nKoelble joined Death when its founder, Chuck Schuldiner, whom he had met in high school in the Orlando area, was recommended to him through a friend working at a local music store.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://agoraphobic-news.com/interviews_view.php?url=exclusive_interview_with_bobby_koelble_of_death_death_to_all_tour|title=Exclusive interview with Bobby Koelble of Death/Death To All Tour|work=Agoraphobic News|date=December 22, 2015|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nKoelble toured with the band in the United States, Canada, Europe, and Japan, before Death was disbanded. \n\nHe performs with [[The Jazz Professors]], a jazz group with two Top-20 Billboard Jazz albums.\n\n===Teaching===\n* Adjunct Professor, Jazz Guitar - [[University of Central Florida]] (2007\u2013) \n* Adjunct Professor, Jazz Guitar - [[Rollins College]] (1998\u2013) \n* Visiting professor, Seminole Community College (2003\u20132005)<ref name=ucf/>\n\n===Other=== \nInstructor/Consultant - [[TalkingTabs]], producing guitar instruction for the blind and learning disabled.<ref name=ucf/>\n\n==Performed with==\n* [[Death_(metal_band)|Death]]\n* [[Sam Rivers]]\n* [[Danny Gottlieb]]\n* [[Chris Potter (jazz saxophonist)|Chris Potter]]\n* [[The Jazz Professors]]\n* Junkie Rush\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koelble, Bobby}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Newark, New Jersey]]\n\n\n{{improve categories|date=February 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American guitarist}}\n'''Bobby Koelble''' (born September 15, 1968) is an American guitarist who performs in the [[death metal]], [[Blues music|blues]], [[Funk music|funk]] and [[jazz]] genres, and as a freelance, studio musician. He is probably best known for his performances with the [[Death metal]] band [[Death (metal band)|Death]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.metal-archives.com/artists/Bobby_Koelble/72714|title=Bobby Koelble - Encyclopaedia Metallum: The Metal Archives|website=www.metal-archives.com}}</ref><ref name=moapril26>{{cite web|url=https://www.orangeobserver.com/article/guitarist-bobby-koelble-explores-music-at-winter-parks-blue-bamboo-center-for-the-arts|title=Guitarist Bobby Koelble explores music at Winter Park\u2019s Blue Bamboo Center for the Arts|author=Tim Freed|work=Orange Observer|date=April 26, 2018|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref> The album he played on, ''[[Symbolic (Death album)|Symbolic]]'', was regarded by [[Joel McIver]] of British music magazine ''[[Record Collector]]'' \"as close to flawless as metal gets.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://recordcollectormag.com/reviews/symbolic|title=Death \u2013 Symbolic|work=[[Record Collector]]|first=Joel|last=McIver|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nBorn in [[Newark, New Jersey]], Koelble\u2019s family moved to central Florida when he was three years old. He began playing the organ when he was seven. By thirteen, Koelble transitioned to guitar, inspired by hard rock banks like [[Van Halen]] and [[AC/DC]]. His evolution into metal music was influenced by bands like [[Iron Maiden]], [[Motorhead|Mot\u00f6rhead]] and [[Judas Priest]].<ref name=moapril26/>\n\n==Education==\nKoelble graduated the [[Berklee College of Music]] with a bachelors\u2019 degree in performance.<ref name=ucf>{{cite web|url=https://music.cah.ucf.edu/staff.php?id=255|title=CF Music -  Faculty Page - Bobby Koeble|work=[[University of Central Florida]]|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nKoelble works on original projects, as a leader, and performs for other groups as freelancer, and in studio work.\n\n===Performance===\nKoelble is best known for his time in the latter years of Death (1994-1996), the influential band that defined death metal.\n\nKoelble joined Death when its founder, Chuck Schuldiner, whom he had met in high school in the Orlando area, was recommended to him through a friend working at a local music store.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://agoraphobic-news.com/interviews_view.php?url=exclusive_interview_with_bobby_koelble_of_death_death_to_all_tour|title=Exclusive interview with Bobby Koelble of Death/Death To All Tour|work=Agoraphobic News|date=December 22, 2015|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nKoelble toured with the band in the United States, Canada, Europe, and Japan, before Death was disbanded. \n\nHe performs with [[The Jazz Professors]], a jazz group with two Top-20 Billboard Jazz albums.\n\n===Teaching===\n* Adjunct Professor, Jazz Guitar - [[University of Central Florida]] (2007\u2013) \n* Adjunct Professor, Jazz Guitar - [[Rollins College]] (1998\u2013) \n* Visiting professor, Seminole Community College (2003\u20132005)<ref name=ucf/>\n\n===Other=== \nInstructor/Consultant - [[TalkingTabs]], producing guitar instruction for the blind and learning disabled.<ref name=ucf/>\n\n==Performed with==\n* [[Death_(metal_band)|Death]]\n* [[Sam Rivers]]\n* [[Danny Gottlieb]]\n* [[Chris Potter (jazz saxophonist)|Chris Potter]]\n* [[The Jazz Professors]]\n* Junkie Rush\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Koelble, Bobby}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American guitarists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Newark, New Jersey]]\n\n\n{{improve categories|date=February 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Cyfal", "label": "safe", "comment": "direct link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bobby_Koelble"}
{"title_page": "Haifa Zangana", "text_new": "'''Haifa Zangana''' (born 1950 in [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]])<ref name=HaifaFacts>{{cite web | url =http://www.stateofnature.org/poemsIraq.html | title =Haifa Facts | accessdate =2007-08-27 | publisher =stateofnature.org}}</ref> is an [[Iraq]]i novelist, author, artist, and political activist, best known for writing ''Women on a Journey: Between Baghdad and London''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/comment/story/0,,1550325,00.html | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Chewing on meaningless words | first=Haifa | last=Zangana | date=2005-08-17 | accessdate=2010-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.selvesandothers.org/view547.html |title=Haifa Zangana<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2007-08-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927024312/http://www.selvesandothers.org/view547.html |archive-date=2007-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nHaifa Zangana was born in Baghdad to a Kurdish father from the northern city of Kirkuk and Arabic mother from Karbala. Her family home was always full of relatives from the northern cities. She was seven when the Iraq Revolution of 1958 resulted in the country gaining independence. She was a teenager when the Ba'ath Party assumed power.\n\nIn the 1960s, she was part of a protest rally to release the Algerian political prisoner, Jamila Buhrayd. As a young Iraqi growing up in an uncertain environment, she noted that:\n\n{{blockquote|\"The woman freedom fighter looms large in the Arab world. For us teenagers, it was Jamilah, not a pop-singer nor a super model that served as a role model\"<ref>Zangana, H., ''City of Widows: An Iraqi Woman's Account of War and Resistance,'' [Author's Biographical Notes], Seven Stories Press, 2011 [E-book edition], n.p.</ref>}}\n\nIn the early 1970s, as a young activist in the [[Iraqi Communist Party]] Haifa was imprisoned by the Baath regime at [[Abu Ghraib prison|Abu Ghraib]]. She was one of a group of female resisters who were imprisoned for distributing leaflets at their university and for attending political meetings. They were captured and tortured and forced to sign confessions, but Zangana managed to escape execution. When she was released from prison, she stayed in Iraq to continue her studies. <ref>Al-Hassan Golley, N., ''Arab Women's Lives Retold: Exploring Identity Through Writing'', Syracuse University Press, 2007, pp 189-90; Abdel Nasser, T., ''Literary Autobiography and Arab National Struggles'', Edinburgh University Press, 2017, [E-Book edition], n.p.</ref>\n\nShe graduated from [[University of Baghdad|Baghdad University]] and the School of Pharmacy in 1974. After graduating, she was appointed to manage the Red Crescent's nascent pharmaceutical unit in Dummar, near Damascus. This was a challenging role due to lack of funds. The work required continual movement between Syria and Lebanon.<ref>Zangana, H., ''City of Widows: An Iraqi Woman's Account of War and Resistance'', [Author's Biographical Notes], Seven Stories Press, 2011; It may be worth noting that this book contains a detailed biographical sketch of the author's resistance activities not summarised here.</ref>\n\nShe left Iraq for political reasons, first moving to Syria where she continued to work for the Palestinian Red Crescent. She relocated to [[United Kingdom|Britain]] in 1976 and has settled there.<ref>[http://www.brusselstribunal.org/bios/Zangana.htm \"Questioning the New Imperial World Order\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nAs a painter and writer she participated in the eighties in various European and American publications and group exhibitions, with one-woman shows in London and [[Iceland]]. She is also a frequent commentator ''[[The Guardian]]'', and a contributor to European and Arabic publications such as  ''Red pepper'', ''Al Ahram weekly'' and ''Al Quds'' (weekly comment), and is a founding member of the [[International Association of Contemporary Iraqi Studies]] and a member of the advisory board of the [[Brussel\u2019s Tribunal on Iraq]]. She was an advisor for the [http://hdr.undp.org/sites/default/files/rbas_ahdr2005_en.pdf UNDP Report \"Towards the Rise of Women in the Arab World\"] (2005) and as a consultant for [https://www.unescwa.org/ ESCWA] (United Nations Economic and Social Commission for Western Asia) she contributed to the \"Arab Integration\" report and the \"Towards Justice in the Arab world\" report which was withdrawn by the UN general secretary.\n\nZangana has consistently drawn on her experience of living in exile to inform her artwork and writing.<ref>Al-Hassan Golley, N., ''Arab Women's Lives Retold: Exploring Identity Through Writing'', Syracuse University Press, 2007, p. 189</ref>. She has also been active in helping other women to use language to explore their lives, as in the case of Palestinian ex-prisoners.<ref>Zangana, H. (ed.), \"Party for Thaera: Palestinian women writing life {{cite book |last1=Zangana |first1=H. |title=Party for Thaera: Palestinian women writing life |date=2017 |publisher=E-Kutub}}</ref>. Her work with women who were formerly political prisoners in Tunisia focuses on helping them to write their own experiences as part of a [[transitional justice]] process.\n\n==Works==\n'''Books'''\n* ''Party for Thaera: Palestinian women writing life'' [in Arabic] (2017)\n* ''City of Widows: An Iraqi Woman's Account of War and Resistance'' (2008), [[Seven Stories Press]]\n* ''Women on a Journey: Between Baghdad and London'' (2001)\n* ''Keys to a City'' (2000)\n* ''The Presence of Others'' (1999)\n* ''Beyond What the Eye Sees'' (1997)\n* ''Dreaming of Baghdad'' (2009)\n* ''Through the Vast Halls of Memory'' (1991)\n* ''The Torturer in the Mirror'', co authored with Ramsey Clark, Thomas Ehrlich Reifer, Seven Stories, NY, 2010\n* ''Iraqi Women Hair Braids'' co-authored with D.U, Dar Fadhaat, (Amman, 2013)\n* ''Arab Women Political Participation'', (Arab Unity Studies Centre, Beirut, 2012)\n\n'''Chapters in books'''\n\n* \"The developing role of colonial feminists in Iraq\", in: ''Arab Feminism'', Jean Makdisi, Noha Bayoumi & Rafif Sidawi (eds), I.B.Tauris, 2014\n* \"Iraq\" , in: ''Dispatches from the Arab Spring,'' Paul Amar & Vijay Prashad (eds), University of Minnesota Press, 2013\n* \"Women and learning in the Iraqi War Zone\", in: ''Women, War, Violence and Learning'', Shahrazad Mojab (ed.), Routledge, 2010.\n* \"Abu Ghraib: Prison as a Collective Memory\" in: ''Contested Spaces'', ed Louise Purbrick, Palgrave, 2007.\n* \"Song of Resistance\" in:''War with No End\u201d, STW & Verso 2007.\n* \"Behind the mask\" in: \u201cDr Rice in the house\u201d, ed Amy Scholder, Seven Stories, 2007.\n* \"Democracy Strangled at Birth\", in: \u201cAsking we walk\u201d, ed Corinne Kumar, Streelekha, 2007. \n* \u201cThe three Cyclops of Empire: Targeting the Fabric of Iraqi Society\u201d, in: ''Empire\u2019s Law,'' Pluto, Feb- 2006\n* \u201cColonial Feminist: From Washington to Baghdad\u201d, in: ''Barriers to Reconciliation'', Washington D.C University Press, 2006.\n* \"The Right to Rule Ourselves\",  in: ''Not One More Death\u201d, [ A collection of writings against the Iraq war/ occupation], STW and Verso- March 2006.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Culture of Iraq]]\n* [[Iraqi art]]\n* [[Islamic art]]\n* [[List of Iraqi artists]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.versobooks.com/authors/210-210-haifa-zangana Author page at Verso]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/comment/story/0,,1550325,00.html Haifa Zangana Article:Chewing on meaningless words]\n*Solitude and dream: literature post-9/11, interview with Haifa Zangana, Open Democracy [https://www.opendemocracy.net/frances-pinter-haifa-zanaga/solitude-and-dream-literature-post-911]\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zangana, Haifa}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Artists from Baghdad]]\n[[Category:Artist authors]]\n[[Category:British artists]]\n[[Category:British women artists]]\n[[Category:Iraqi contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Iraqi emigrants to the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Iraqi women artists]]\n[[Category:Iraqi women writers]]\n[[Category:Iraqi novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Writers from Baghdad]]\n", "text_old": "'''Haifa Zangana''' (born 1950 in [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]])<ref name=HaifaFacts>{{cite web | url =http://www.stateofnature.org/poemsIraq.html | title =Haifa Facts | accessdate =2007-08-27 | publisher =stateofnature.org}}</ref> is an [[Iraq]]i novelist, author, artist, and political activist, best known for writing ''Women on a Journey: Between Baghdad and London''.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/comment/story/0,,1550325,00.html | work=The Guardian | location=London | title=Chewing on meaningless words | first=Haifa | last=Zangana | date=2005-08-17 | accessdate=2010-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.selvesandothers.org/view547.html |title=Haifa Zangana<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2007-08-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927024312/http://www.selvesandothers.org/view547.html |archive-date=2007-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nHaifa Zangana was born in Baghdad to a Kurdish father from the northern city of Kirkuk and Arabic mother from Karbala. Her family home was always full of relatives from the northern cities. She was seven when the Iraq Revolution of 1958 resulted in the country gaining independence. She was a teenager when the Ba'ath Party assumed power.\n\nIn the 1960s, she was part of a protest rally to release the Algerian political prisoner, Jamila Buhrayd. As a young Iraqi growing up in an uncertain environment, she noted that:\n\n{{blockquote|\"The woman freedom fighter looms large in the Arab world. For us teenagers, it was Jamilah, not a pop-singer nor a super model that served as a role model\"<ref>Zangana, H., ''City of Widows: An Iraqi Woman's Account of War and Resistance,'' [Author's Biographical Notes], Seven Stories Press, 2011 [E-book edition], n.p.</ref>}}\n\nIn the early 1970s, as a young activist in the [[Iraqi Communist Party]] Haifa was imprisoned by the Baath regime at [[Abu Ghraib prison|Abu Ghraib]]. She was one of a group of female resisters who were imprisoned for distributing leaflets at their university and for attending political meetings. They were captured and tortured and forced to sign confessions, but Zangana managed to escape execution. When she was released from prison, she stayed in Iraq to continue her studies. <ref>Al-Hassan Golley, N., ''Arab Women's Lives Retold: Exploring Identity Through Writing'', Syracuse University Press, 2007, pp 189-90; Abdel Nasser, T., ''Literary Autobiography and Arab National Struggles'', Edinburgh University Press, 2017, [E-Book edition], n.p.</ref>\n\nShe graduated from [[University of Baghdad|Baghdad University]] and the School of Pharmacy in 1974. After graduating, she was appointed to manage the Red Crescent's nascent pharmaceutical unit in Dummar, near Damascus. This was a challenging role due to lack of funds. The work required continual movement between Syria and Lebanon.<ref>Zangana, H., ''City of Widows: An Iraqi Woman's Account of War and Resistance'', [Author's Biographical Notes], Seven Stories Press, 2011; It may be worth noting that this book contains a detailed biographical sketch of the author's resistance activities not summarised here.</ref>\n\nShe left Iraq for political reasons, first moving to Syria where she continued to work for the Palestinian Red Crescent. She relocated to [[United Kingdom|Britain]] in 1976 and has settled there.<ref>[http://www.brusselstribunal.org/bios/Zangana.htm \"Questioning the New Imperial World Order\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nAs a painter and writer she participated in the eighties in various European and American publications and group exhibitions, with one-woman shows in London and [[Iceland]]. She is also a frequent commentator ''[[The Guardian]]'', and a contributor to European and Arabic publications such as  ''Red pepper'', ''Al Ahram weekly'' and ''Al Quds'' (weekly comment), and is a founding member of the [[International Association of Contemporary Iraqi Studies]] and a member of the advisory board of the [[Brussel\u2019s Tribunal on Iraq]]. She was an advisor for the [http://hdr.undp.org/sites/default/files/rbas_ahdr2005_en.pdf UNDP Report \"Towards the Rise of Women in the Arab World\"] (2005) and as a consultant for [https://www.unescwa.org/ ESCWA] (United Nations Economic and Social Commission for Western Asia) she contributed to the \"Arab Integration\" report and the \"Towards Justice in the Arab world\" report which was withdrawn by the UN general secretary.\n\nZangana has consistently drawn on her experience of living in exile to inform her artwork and writing.<ref>Al-Hassan Golley, N., ''Arab Women's Lives Retold: Exploring Identity Through Writing'', Syracuse University Press, 2007, p. 189</ref>. She has also been active in helping other women to use language to explore their lives, as in the case of Palestinian ex-prisoners.<ref>Zangana, H. (ed.), \"Party for Thaera: Palestinian women writing life {{cite book |last1=Zangana |first1=H. |title=Party for Thaera: Palestinian women writing life |date=2017 |publisher=E-Kutub}}</ref>. Her work with women who were formerly political prisoners in Tunisia focuses on helping them to write their own experiences as part of a transitional justice process.\n\n==Works==\n'''Books'''\n* ''Party for Thaera: Palestinian women writing life'' [in Arabic] (2017)\n* ''City of Widows: An Iraqi Woman's Account of War and Resistance'' (2008), [[Seven Stories Press]]\n* ''Women on a Journey: Between Baghdad and London'' (2001)\n* ''Keys to a City'' (2000)\n* ''The Presence of Others'' (1999)\n* ''Beyond What the Eye Sees'' (1997)\n* ''Dreaming of Baghdad'' (2009)\n* ''Through the Vast Halls of Memory'' (1991)\n* ''The Torturer in the Mirror'', co authored with Ramsey Clark, Thomas Ehrlich Reifer, Seven Stories, NY, 2010\n* ''Iraqi Women Hair Braids'' co-authored with D.U, Dar Fadhaat, (Amman, 2013)\n* ''Arab Women Political Participation'', (Arab Unity Studies Centre, Beirut, 2012)\n\n'''Chapters in books'''\n\n* \"The developing role of colonial feminists in Iraq\", in: ''Arab Feminism'', Jean Makdisi, Noha Bayoumi & Rafif Sidawi (eds), I.B.Tauris, 2014\n* \"Iraq\" , in: ''Dispatches from the Arab Spring,'' Paul Amar & Vijay Prashad (eds), University of Minnesota Press, 2013\n* \"Women and learning in the Iraqi War Zone\", in: ''Women, War, Violence and Learning'', Shahrazad Mojab (ed.), Routledge, 2010.\n* \"Abu Ghraib: Prison as a Collective Memory\" in: ''Contested Spaces'', ed Louise Purbrick, Palgrave, 2007.\n* \"Song of Resistance\" in:''War with No End\u201d, STW & Verso 2007.\n* \"Behind the mask\" in: \u201cDr Rice in the house\u201d, ed Amy Scholder, Seven Stories, 2007.\n* \"Democracy Strangled at Birth\", in: \u201cAsking we walk\u201d, ed Corinne Kumar, Streelekha, 2007. \n* \u201cThe three Cyclops of Empire: Targeting the Fabric of Iraqi Society\u201d, in: ''Empire\u2019s Law,'' Pluto, Feb- 2006\n* \u201cColonial Feminist: From Washington to Baghdad\u201d, in: ''Barriers to Reconciliation'', Washington D.C University Press, 2006.\n* \"The Right to Rule Ourselves\",  in: ''Not One More Death\u201d, [ A collection of writings against the Iraq war/ occupation], STW and Verso- March 2006.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Culture of Iraq]]\n* [[Iraqi art]]\n* [[Islamic art]]\n* [[List of Iraqi artists]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.versobooks.com/authors/210-210-haifa-zangana Author page at Verso]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/comment/story/0,,1550325,00.html Haifa Zangana Article:Chewing on meaningless words]\n*Solitude and dream: literature post-9/11, interview with Haifa Zangana, Open Democracy [https://www.opendemocracy.net/frances-pinter-haifa-zanaga/solitude-and-dream-literature-post-911]\n{{Auth